note: CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-07T03:24Z as well as in later frames of C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME appears very faint in white light imagery. The best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A indicate that this event may originate from the vicinity of S15E30, however there is no definitive source seen on the disk for this event. There are a number of speculative sources including field line loop movement and brightening from AR 3781 (S13E42) as seen in SDO AIA 94.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption seen on the northeast limb at about N17E90 in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284. Field line movement and a small bright loop can be seen as early as 2024-08-07T00:38Z in GOES SUVI 284 and 2024-08-07T00:58Z in SDO AIA 193. The small loop of field lines that brighten is located at an apparent latitude of N17 and is on or very close to the East limb. There are faint opening field lines surrounding this loop seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at roughly 2024-08-07T01:03Z and extending from apparent latitudes of about S05 to N20 on the E limb. The exact location of source may possibly extend beyond the E limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME first seen by SOHO LASCO C2 in the NW beginning at 2024-08-07T03:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. Possible source is a C8.5 flare from N05W85 peaking at 2024-08-07T02:01Z as seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 in real-time due to a data gap starting at 2024-08-07T14:09Z. Eruption with M4.5 flare from AR 3774 (approx. S10W22), field line movement, and possible faint EUV wave visible in SDO AIA 193. Opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Backsided halo CME visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 in real-time due to a data gap from 2024-08-07T14:09Z. The source is not seen in available EUV imagery, and is believed to be backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is an M5.0 flare peaking at 2024-08-07T18:54Z from AR 3777. The start of the CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-08-07T17:23Z to 23:09Z. Dimming, opening field lines are seen in SDO AIA 193, and the eruption appears to be directed towards the southeast. A possible faint, separate halo component may also be seen in early frames of SOHO LASCO C2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-08T04:48Z as well as in later frames by STEREO A COR2. This event is not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C3 as it may be too faint or obscured by the pylon. Possible source is wider field line opening seen beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Outflow CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-08T05:12Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this eruption/outflow may be the continuous movement and restructuring of field lines between ARs 3780 (S09E25) and 3777 (S09W08) as seen in SDO AIA 94.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint halo CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C3 beginning at approximately 2024-08-08T05:30Z. This event is too faint to confidently track in SOHO LASCO C2 or STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is an M1.3 class flare from AR 3777 (S05W15) peaking at 2024-08-08T04:41Z as seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Halo CME first seen by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-08T20:00Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The beginning of this event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-08-08T19:38Z to  2024-08-08T22:53Z. The source of this CME is an X1.3 class flare from AR 3777 (S05W25) that peaked at 2024-08-08T19:36Z. This flare can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with an EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. Resulting field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-09T01:25Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is an eruption of a filament on the NE limb that lifts off at approximately 23:09Z from approximately N40E60 as seen in SDO AIA 304. Field line opening can also be seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The first portion of this filament erupts at approximately 22:43Z and resulting in an earlier CME, CME: 2024-08-08T23:24Z which measured below 250 km/s.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME with the front best seen in SOHO LASCO C2 but also traceable in a couple of early timestamps in C3. The CME front is not seen in STEREO A (although imagery is available).  No source for the CME was found on disk but there is a tiny post-eruptive arcade seen from behind the west limb in AIA195/131 starting around 2024-08-09T05Z, possibly indicating a source behind the west limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely faint CME, barely seen in white light imagery and better seen in difference imagery. No clear source has been found on the Earth-facing disk, however an extremely faint dimming, followed by equally faint post-eruptive arcades is seen in AIA 193/211 centered roughly around (N30E35) starting with 2024-08-09T07Z. There is also a faint movement of field lines behind/on the eastern limb but the fit with two coronagraphs does not fit the close to the limb source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The start of the CME is not visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in real-time due to a data gap from approx. 2024-08-09T11:42Z-16:42Z. The source may be similar to the potential source of CME: 2024-08-09T08:24:00-CME-001, with faint dimming and post-eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 193 and 211 around 2024-08-09T09:36Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an M4.5 flare peaking at 2024-08-09T21:23Z from AR 3774 (approx. S05W40). Eruption with rising/opening field lines and dimming are best seen in SDO AIA 193, GOES 284, and STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a clear front only in a few early timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, with fuzzy front in C3 and STEREO A COR2. The clear source is an opening of field lines in SDO AIA 171 beyond NW limb starting at 2024-08-09T23:54Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the NE in STEREO A COR2. It later overlaps in the field of view with CMEs 2024-08-10T03:12Z and 2024-08-10T03:24Z. The CME could not be reliably tracked in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, possibly due to the overlapping features of the later CMEs. The source could not be found, and it may be backsided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and the NE of STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear, but may be one of a couple faint candidate source eruptions on the disk, best seen in GOES SUVI 284. The first starts around 2024-08-10T02:42Z with dimming near N15W30 starting. There may also be eruptive activity from Active Regions 3781 or 3783 in the NE, seen starting around 2024-08-10T02:34Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Partial halo CME faintly seen towards the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and the NE of STEREO A COR2. Overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-08-10T03:12:00-CME-001. The likely source is an M5.3 flare peaking at 2024-08-10T02:37Z from AR 3780 (approx. S08W02) with associated eruption with dimming and post-eruptive arcades best seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright, slow CME seen to the far north in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is on the far-side of the sun, at an apparent high latitude. Observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 and well in GOES SUVI 284 as field lines first opening over the NNE limb around 2024-08-10T22:31Z, and a secondary, wider field line opening starting around 2024-08-11T00:51Z. This eruption is wide and slow, and evolves into a dimpled front in the furthest coronagraph imagery from its the initial frames as the filamentary material is uniquely observed unfurling in coronagraphs.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow loop CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and possibly extremely faintly in STEREO A COR2. There is no discernable distinct source. This CME overlaps and overtakes a much slower CME first seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-08-10T21:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Thin CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain, not directly observed in SDO, GOES, or STEREO A EUV imagery. However, the CME does fit around N20W54 in swpc_cat between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A, so this is used as the source, with some medium confidence via the triangulated fit.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This faint CME is seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. No discernable source signatures are visible in SDO AIA or GOES SUVI imagery. This eruption possibly correlates to an estimated M1.0 flare observed in STIX data, with estimated peak time at roughly 2024-08-11T06:24Z and located beyond on SE limb of the Earth-facing disk (on the SW limb as seen from Solar Orbiter). This CME overlaps with CME:2024-08-11T07:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and extremely faintly in STEREO A COR2. This CME overlaps with CME:2024-08-11T07:00Z; both CMEs are believed to be from the same source. No discernable source signatures are visible in SDO AIA or GOES SUVI imagery. This eruption possibly correlates to an estimated M1.0 flare observed in STIX data, with estimated peak time at roughly 2024-08-11T06:24Z and located beyond on SE limb of the Earth-facing disk (on the SW limb as seen from Solar Orbiter).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This narrow CME is seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and faintly in STEREO A COR2. The source is a small filament eruption on or just beyond SE limb accompanied by opening field lines, as seen in SDO AIA 304/171/193 starting at about 2024-08-11T09:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint narrow jet visible in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO/LASCO coronagraphs, with the front mostly seen in the running difference imagery.  No clear source for this CME has been found on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, jet-like CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. There are no clear source signatures seen on this disk for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Thin CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. Source is a region of the disk centered ~S36E50, with an eruption observed in SDO AIA 304 as thin ejecting filament material and brightening of the surface starting around 2024-08-12T07:33Z, with field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T08:24Z, as well as in later frames by STEREO A COR2. This event was too faint to be seen clearly in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is a small eruption from the vicinity of AR 3785 (S18E45). Material is seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA 304 and minor post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. Source is a region of the disk centered ~N35E75, with an eruption observed as brightening of the disk in SDO AIA 304 starting around 2024-08-12T08:42Z, and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, jet-like CME first seen in the S by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T12:36Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this eruption is a jet of material seen clearly in GOES SUVI 304 lifting off from approx. S20E90 beginning at approximately 2024-08-12T12:00Z exhibiting strong Southern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME first seen to the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T19:00Z as well as in later frames by C3. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available due to a data gap from 2024-08-12T14:38Z to 2024-08-12T22:38Z. Possible source of this eruption is field line opening from AR 3780 (S11W30) exhibiting Southern deflection beginning at approximately 2024-08-12T18:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T21:48Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a jet of material seen in GOES SUVI 304 beginning at approximately 19:30Z from the vicinity of S30W90 but exhibiting Southeastern deflection. Field line opening can also be seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. There is no STEREO A EUVI data for this source signature due to a data gap from 2024-08-12T14:05Z to 2024-08-12T22:55Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-13T00:12Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this eruption is a thin release of material from approximately S30W90+ that exhibits strong Southeastern deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor jet CME seen to the south in C2, C3, and COR2A, especially in running difference imagery. May be associated with a very minor eruption at far southern latitudes on the Earth-facing disk seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 04:03Z near S70W40.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-13T06:24Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a long, thin eruption off of the SW limb (approx. S30W90+) exhibiting strong Southeastern deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Opening field lines can also be clearly seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the east, clearer seen in STEREO A coronagraph imagery. It has two lobes moving in unison. The source of this event seems to be indicated by the opening of field lines on/near the east limb, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171 imagery after 2024-08-13T09Z, and by a small area of post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 284 close to (S04E70) at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A relatively wide CME where the source is a slow but relatively significant filament eruption in the SW centered ~S30W45, seen as two waves of ejecta/dimming/opening of field lines/post-eruptive arcades in the SW in AIA 193/304. This is preceded by a C6.6 flare from AR 3780 peaking at 2024-08-14T07:37Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint halo, with the front not seen in white light imagery but seen distinctly in SOHO difference imagery, both C2 and C3 (and not only in the early timestamps). The event is fully covered by a large data gap in STEREO A COR2. Its source could potentially be the faint eruption north of AR 3774 centered around (N28E12) and seen as very minor light dimming in AIA 193 between 2024-08-13T08Z and 14Z, however these coronal signatures seem too faint for a noticeable halo. Alternatively, the source could be far-sided. No coronal signatures indicating backsided CME have been found on/behind limb in AIA imagery, but there is a long-duration C8-class flare on the far side seen by STIX instrument on Solar Orbiter and peaking around 13:40Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet CME seen to the south in SOHO C2/C3 imagery. The source is not clear as there is no evidence of moving field lines off the southern limb in available GOES/SDO imagers, so potentially the source is located on the far side of the Sun.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fairly narrow CME seen to the north at very high northern latitudes associated with a filament eruption that is seen best in SDO 171/304 after 2024-08-13T18:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Complex CME seen to the southwest made up of several disjoint fronts that all seemingly move together, the leading edge begins to become more diffuse in later frames. Associated with rapidly opening and breaking magnetic field lines near the vicinity of AR3777 (S10W86).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a narrow ejection of material from a small region near S08W70. This small eruption begins at approximately 2024-08-14T02:30Z and appears to exhibit some deflection to the NW as seen in SDO AIA 304. This CME overlaps with CME: 2024-08-14T04:12Z in later frames preventing analysis further into the field of view.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-14T03:48Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source appears to be a small filament eruption located at approx. S30W100 beginning around 2024-08-14T01:50Z exhibiting a more Southern deflection as seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraph imagery. The source is likely an M4.4 flare and eruption from Active Region 13777 (S04W89) starting around 2024-08-14T03:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An opening of field lines is visible near the western limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 05:30Z as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: First CME in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs. No coronal signatures on disk have been found; there are some coronal signatures indicating that there were multiple eruptions around this time on/behind the limb, but these consecutive CMEs do not fit with two coronagraphs with longitudes close to/above 90 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo directed towards the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is visible mostly to the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an X1.1 flare and eruption from Active Region 13784 (N14E03) starting around 2024-08-14T06:27Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is observed in SDO AIA 171 and 193 surrounding the eruption site, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 08:30Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint jet-like CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-14T09:12Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen on the Earth facing disk, however some faint field line opening can be seen in SDO AIA 193, leading to a likely far sided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Second in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs with no coronal signatures on disk but measuring about 65 deg long.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Third in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs with no coronal signatures on disk but measuring about 65 deg long.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Forth in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs with no coronal signatures on disk but measuring about 65 deg long.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint and narrow CME seen to the E in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2. Extremely faint in C3. Source is opening field lines on the E limb seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-08-14T23:30Z, from AR 13790 (S10E80).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Extremely faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Exact source is uncertain, but is likely associated with the continuous field line movement seen on the west limb in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME in the northwest. Its clear source is a beautiful eruption that looks like a loop and is seen on or just behind the northwest limb starting around 2024-08-15T09:30Z, according to the SDO AIA 304/171 and GOES SUVI 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. Not visible in COR2 due to a data gap in STEREO A lasting from 2024-08-15T17:53Z to 2024-08-15T22:23Z and due to the faintness of this event. Source is a small eruption seen from beyond the N/NE limb starting at 2024-08-15T18:03Z in SDO AIA 304, at an apparent latitude of N60. Small amount of ejecta seen in SDO AIA 171 starting at 18:18Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-16T02:00Z as well as in later frames by SOHO LASCO C3. This event is too faint to be reliably tracked in STEREO A COR2. There is not distinct source seen for this event however small eruptive activity is seen in the vicinity of AR 3790 (S14E70) at this time as seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Slow streamer blowout CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at approximately 2024-08-16T10:00Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. Field line loop movement can be seen around the central West limb in GOES SUVI 171 and 284. A second more inner loop can be seen as part of this structure, however outermore feature is much more pronounced.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR 2 imagery for a few frames prior to a data gap starting at 2024-08-16T17:53Z. note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a small eruption near the western limb starting around 2024-08-17T06:20Z seen best in SDO AIA 304 imagery.

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source of this CME could potentially be a filament eruption visible along the N/NW limb believed to be on the far-side of the sun as seen in SDO/AIA 304. There are a few fronts visible in the coronagraphs that appear associated with this eruption, this front is first seen starting around 16:00Z while an earlier much slower front is seen starting around 15:12Z.

note: A very faint CME following the faster 2024-08-17T19:12Z CME. This CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO and its front is not seen in white light imagery in any coronagraph. note: The start of this CME is likely much earlier but the front is not seen in C2. It is another (the narrowest) outflow from the fast 2024-08-17T19:12Z CME. The start of this CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2; its front is not seen in C2 difference imagery, but is seen in C3 and later COR2A difference imagery as a narrow blip. No source has been found in EUV imagery.

Data gap in STEREO A lasting from 2023-08-18T14:23Z to 2024-08-18T22:38Z obscures a few early STEREO A frames of this CME.

The source of this event appears to be a large far-sided eruption, evidenced by wide opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 beginning at approximately 2024-08-22T06:19Z and the possible remnants of filamentary material seen in GOES SUVI 304.

The source for this CME is uncertain, but thanks to the two frames in STEREO COR2A a triangulation was made around S42W24 via swpc_cat, with some speculation due to the single-frame triangulation.

note: Faint CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, though very faint in C2 to the point of being unable to distinctively define its start time around the occulting disk, so T17:24Z was used as the best reference for visibility in C2. No source observed for this CME in EUV imagery.

note: CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. The source appears to be far-sided, observed best as field line movement on the east limb starting around 2024-08-24T20:18Z in SDO AIA 171, likely deflecting northward observing its travel path from SOHO LASCO C2 to C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME tracking/overlapping with outflows following the 2024-08-24T21:12Z CME and similarly consisting of two lobes moving at the same pace. No on-disk source was found for this CME in the EUV imagery, so it is likely farsided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Streamer blowout CME to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The start time of the CME could be as early as ~10Z, as that's when the shape first starts appearing in difference imagery, however it doesn't quite start progressing out in the field of view until roughly 12:12Z. The source appears to be moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284 in the SE quadrant of the Earth-facing disk with notable changes in the corona's structure over the course of several hours. Most notably, these changes are visible starting around 14:00Z. Brightening is visible on the disk starting around 15:00Z with continued restructuring of the corona for several hours after. Additionally, the CME structure appears to be visible in the field lines off the SE limb, fairly stationary as early as 2024-08-25T17:00Z and is released during this restructuring starting around 2024-08-26T12:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-28T04:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is the eruption of a loop like filament sitting on or just beyond the East limb centered at approximately S10E90 as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94 and 131. This filament erupted in two portions, the first appearing as a streamer outflow, followed by the main expulsion of material. In the coronagraphs, this appears as two leading edges, a further out one that is lopsided and faint and a closer in one that is more central and bright. Parameters of this event are based on the more central, brightest portion of this CME, as that is where the bulk of the material resides.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-28T11:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk apart from some minor field line movement seen in the NE in SDO AIA 171. Event does not exhibit a clear and distinct leading edge.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-28T12:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. A majority of this CME is obscured by data gaps (SOHO: 28/14:36Z to 29/04:35Z, COR2A: 28/14:23Z to 28/23:09Z), so analysis of this event is based solely on later frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is dimming seen around N45W40 as seen in SDO AIA 211 beginning at approximately 28/11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-08-28T18:15Z. There is no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery available for this event due to a data gap from 28/14:36Z to 29/04:35Z. The source of this CME is clear opening field lines seen along the SE limb by SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284, likely representing a far sided source. However the CME itself is fairly faint.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-29T05:17Z as well as by C3 and STERO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening that appears to stretch from an area of dimming just NE of AR 3803 at approx. N20E60, to beyond the East limb. This field line movement begins at approximately 2024-08-29T04:08Z as seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 195. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2. The source is likely a super minor eruption off/behind the northeast limb seen after 2024-08-29T18:45Z in AIA 304 and as minor moving/opening of field lines in AIA 193. The CME is covered in STEREO A COR2 by a data gap and is seen very faintly in C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A very faint minor CME only seen in a few early timestamps in the SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. The CME front is too faint to discern in LASCO C3 coronagraph. No source was found on the Earth-facing disk for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME in the northeast where the source could be a minor filament eruption centered around N22E47 and spanning from N12E30 to N39E50. The filament is seen in SDO AIA 304 lifting off at 2024-08-29T23:21Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the southeast which possibly consists of two lobes: an earlier, more eastern lobe, and a later, narrower, lobe, directed somewhat more to the south. The source of this CME is the fast opening of and movement of field lines in the corona behind the southeast limb directed, as well as dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 at 2024-08-30T12:27Z. This eruption was also associated with the M3.8 flare from Active Region 13806. There was also a slightly later, slower, eruption from the southeast limb (or from behind the limb), which is seen in SDO AIA 193 after 2024-08-30T12:30Z and which is characterized by a minor ejecta best seen in SDO AIA 304, followed by an opening of field lines behind the limb seen in AIA 171.

note: CME seen to the W in all coronagraphs, but best in STEREO COR2A. The source is not completely clear, and may be a part of some field line movement on/around the west limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning as early as 2024-08-30T18:22Z. This CME is notably extremely faint in SOHO imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. The source is likely a filament eruption just NE of AR 13804, beginning around 2024-08-30T22:48Z and centered around N20E28. Observed as filament material ejecting and brightening in SDO AIA 304, and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source is far-sided, observed best as field line movement over the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-08-31T00:12Z, with initial more southern movement seen starting around 2024-08-30T23:42Z which likely resulted in CME 2024-08-31T01:38Z. This CME's parameters are difficult to pin down, due to an ongoing campaign with SOHO impacting available LASCO C2/C3 imagery for triangulation with STEREO COR2A.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source is far-sided, observed best as field line movement over the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-08-30T23:42Z, with secondary more northern movement seen starting around 2024-08-31T00:12Z which likely resulted in 2024-08-31T00:53Z. This CME's parameters are difficult to pin down, due to an ongoing campaign with SOHO impacting available LASCO C2/C3 imagery for triangulation with STEREO COR2A.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This asymmetrical shaped CME is visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery due to a campaign. The source appears to be moving/opening field lines from beyond the NE limb in SDO/AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-08-31T11:09Z. Multiple loops are seen rising in SDO/AIA 171 which may contribute to the appearance of multiple fronts in coronagraph imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME with kinked front seen to the northwest and eventually southwest in later frames in SOHO, seen to the northeast in STEREO Ahead. May be associated with changes in the northward side of AR3807 with a minor eruption around 02:15Z (S16W19). The spot region then becomes stable after this, from 03Z onward.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a large eruption on the SE limb seen as brightening starting at 2024-09-01T11:06Z in SDO AIA 131, ejection of material at 11:18Z in SDO AIA 304, rapidly opening field lines seen beyond the limb starting at 11:30Z in SDO AIA 171/193. Slow rise and eventual ejection of two overlapping flux rope loops from the southeast limb seen starting as early as 2024-09-01T08:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Long-duration M5.5 flare associated with brightening from post-eruptive arcades that spanned from S20-S30, as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the S/SE following the path of the 2024-09-01T12:23Z CME in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. No clear visible source in SDO/AIA or GOES/SUVI imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption close to the East limb, N15E65, seen starting at 2024-09-02T05:30Z in SDO AIA 171/193, followed by moving/opening field lines seen starting at 2024-09-02T06:03 in SDO AIA 171, as well as post-eruptive arcade starting at 2024-09-02T07:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO C2 and STEREO A, but more predominantly in SOHO imagery, later overlapping with CME:2024-09-02T14:00Z which is seen to the southeast. Seemingly associated with an eruption occurring just before the CME: 2024-09-02T14:00Z from near the same region or farther behind the limb with clear northward deflection, however, fitting for longitudes between 60-70 is poor as the leading edges in SOHO/STEREO A do not overlap well in time, suggesting that this CME is more far-sided than anticipated. Farther longitudes behind the eastern disk do show a stronger leading edge fit and triangulation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. Associated with a contributing portion of an M2.9-class flare and eruption near AR 3813 (S17E62) seen best in SDO 304/193 as a brightening and in 171/193 as brightening with moving field lines. GOES 284 also shows a large bulb-shaped mass emanating from off the southeast limb after the initial brightening.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source was unclear, and possible candidate sources include field line movement seen off the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-09-02T19:00Z, or a possible minor eruption seen near AR 3811 around 2024-09-02T21:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright full asymmetric halo CME in SOHO and a partial northwestern halo in STEREO A, with a fainter but distinct shock front in addition to a very bright bulk. Its source is likely farsided and is indicated by the faint but very wide opening of field lines/restructuring of magnetic field far behind the northwest (extending faintly to southwest) limb, as seen in SDO 193/171 starting at 2024-09-03T08:18Z, also seen in STA EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T14:48Z as well as in later frames by SOHO LASCO C3. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to an ongoing data gap beginning 03/14:38Z with one frame at 03/17:23Z. There is no clear source for this CME seen on the disk, however some minor field line movement can be seen beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 leading to the possibility of this being a far sided event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T15:12Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is limited COR2A data available for this event due to a data gap from 03/14:38Z to 03/17:23Z. The source of this CME is an eruption from AR 3807 (S18W54) beginning at approximately 03/14:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T16:24Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. there is not STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to an ongoing data gap beginning at 03/14:38Z. The source of this CME is wide opening field lines seen off of the West limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning at approx. 03/15:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There is no available STEREO A COR2 data for this event due to a data gap from 2024-09-03T14:38Z to 2024-09-03T22:53Z. A potential source is opening field lines seen in SDO AIA 171/193 starting at 2024-09-03T17:02Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T20:12Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is partially obscured in STEREO A by a data gap from 03/14:38Z to 03/22:53Z. The source of this CME is an area of dimming spanning from N25E30 to N10E03 but is centered around N10E20. Although a majority of the dimming appears to be more central, there are field lines that appear to open more towards the NE as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-04T15:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME appears teardrop shaped in coronagraph imagery, but a faint leading edge is visible. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, however some minor field line opening can be seen off of the West limb in SDO AIA 193 beginning at approximately 04/14:30Z. There is limited STEREO A data available for this event due to an ongoing data gap that began at 04/16:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the northwest in SOHO C2/C3 then becoming more to the north with time. Also seen to the west-northwest in STEREO A COR2A. No obvious sources are seen on the Earth facing disk or off the northwestern limb, so this CME event is likely far-sided relative to the Sun-Earth line.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fairly symmetrical halo CME with brighter portions to the NW in SOHO and NE in STEREO A, first seen around 2024-09-05T07:24Z in SOHO C2. The eruption is very likely on the far-side relative to the Earth-facing solar disk as evidenced by flickering field lines seen best in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 far off the northwest and southwest limbs seen around 2024-09-05T07:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the west. No source has been found on disk in EUV imagery. There is a minor eruptive activity seen on/behind the limb in EUV imagery. There are multiple secondary fronts following the initial front.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, faint CME seen to the southwest in SOHO C2/STEREO A COR2 which may be associated with changes in departing Active Region 3807 (~W97) around 2024-09-06T11:00Z or so as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor puff-like CME seen to the northwest in SOHO C2 and C3 and not seen with available STEREO A COR2 frames due to a data gap. Likely associated with a minor eruption seen near AR3806 (S12W46) seen best in GOES SUVI 304 with northward deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast, narrow CME seen to the south-southwest in SOHO C2, C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not clear, however, one potential source candidate is a filament eruption and surge eruption near the southern portion of the central meridian; it takes place near 16:05Z, which is fairly early compared to when the CME is first seen. Some weakly opening field lines seen best in GOES SUVI 284 just before 18:00Z off the south-southwestern limb could additionally be associated with this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint narrow jet to the southwest. No clear source found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME northeast in SOHO and northwest in STEREO A COR2, with no source found.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME to the south, with coronal signatures that include a wide opening of field lines/departure of mass from the corona best seen in EUVI A 195, high rising post-eruptive arcades and dimming to the west and south of AR 3815 in AIA 193 after the associated flare, as well as a movement of a loop/ejecta and a wide opening of field lines seen in AIA 171 to the south.  In AIA 304 a sigmoid filament structure lights up but it is not clear how much of it departs the corona. The CME displays multiple different consecutive fronts - at the very least it has two lobes (possibly two simultaneous CMEs) - the southern brighter lobe and the more eastern faint one better seen in COR2A (but too faint to see in C3).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with the southeastern front seen in both coronagraphs. It is associated with the M1.6 class flare from Active Region 13815 and is likely not a separate CME but a less prominent lobe (or a  fainter outflow) of the 2024-09-07T07:36Z CME. This front is much fainter than the bright prominent southern lobe of the 2024-09-07T07:36Z CME. This faint front is not seen in the white light SOHO LASCO imagery but is seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery to the southeast. It is also seen faintly in the running difference SOHO LASCO C2 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, faint, jet-like CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C/C2 and STEREO A COR2. The source eruption can be seen from an active region near the limb from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195, best characterized as opening field lines starting at 2024-09-07T10:35Z. It is also visible as opening field lines beyond the west limb in SDO AIA 171/193/335.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is near the west limb in SDO AIA imagery, with an material seen lifting off in GOES SUVI 304 around 2024-09-07T20:16Z. The source eruption was not visible in STEREO A EUV due to a data gap from 2024-09-07T19:35Z-22:35Z. The start of the CME is obscured by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-09-07T20:23Z-22:38Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is believed to be associated with/related to the eruptive activity that resulted in NW partial halo CME:2024-09-08T01:36Z. Dimming is seen in SDO AIA 193 around N40E30, which appears to be an EUV wave propagating from the source of the partial halo eruption, and a dark feature can be seen at the same location in SDO AIA 171, possibly indicating northeastern-directed ejecta at about 2024-09-08T01:17Z, also located at roughly N40E30. This CME is more defined in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 than in STEREO A COR2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and as a partial halo in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption centered near N14W20 which deflects NW as it erupts based on SDO/AIA 304 imagery. The eruption begins around 2024-09-08T00:00Z. A faint EUV wave is visible traveling N/NE of the source location despite the filament material deflecting NW as seen in SDO/AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the W in C2 and STEREO A COR2. Not visible in C3. Leading edge appears brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. Source is opening field lines seen at 2023-09-08T09:15Z just beyond the limb as seen in STEREO-A EUVI 304 and 195 imagery, at about S10.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large, bright lightbulb CME to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a long duration M1.0 flare from AR13806 (~S05W89). Moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 starting around 2024-09-09T00:24Z along the western limb with post-eruptive arcades visible starting around 2024-09-09T02:24Z. The eruption is also visible in GOES SUVI before an eclipse occurs and in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large bright halo CME with bulk to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and following a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source appears to be beyond the eastern limb in SDO/AIA 193 and 211 starting around 2024-09-09T05:00Z with a visible rising loop and clear moving/opening field lines. There is a dimming/reconstruction/EUV wave in the coronal material along the limb. Possible filament material is visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 304 briefly around 2024-09-09T05:10Z. Moving field lines are briefly visible in GOES SUVI 284 before an eclipse occurs.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Slightly faint CME to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption beyond the NE limb starting around 2024-09-09T11:27Z in SDO/AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Associated moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO/AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet-like CME to west in SOHO C2/C3, not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. Associated with an eruption seen off the western limb with departing Active Regions with ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 16:04Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME associated with a long duration M1.2-class flare from Active Region 3814 (N15E10) seen predominantly to the northeast in SOHO C2 imagery and east-northeast in STEREO A COR2. The eruptive signature is seen as a large-broad scale destabilization seen as a surge-like brightening in SDO AIA 131, opening and brightening field lines in GOES SUVI 284 with additional dimming and an EUV wave to the north, and bright, high post-eruptive arcades seen best in SDO AIA 171/193/304. There is a data gap in real-time in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 at the start of the CME from approx. 2024-09-09T21:48Z to 2024-09-10T01:25Z
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The CME starts slowly in coronagraph imagery, and picks up speed around 2024-09-10T08:36Z. The potential source is beyond the east limb as seen in available EUV imagery, but a source signature is unclear. Material liftoff beyond the limb is visible in SDO AIA 304 starting at 2024-09-10T03:00Z, but the timing does not correspond well to this CME. Slow rising field lines from beyond the limb may be visible in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-09-10T07:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The leading edge of the CME fades away quickly in imagery, and overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-09-10T08:36Z. The source is likely a filament eruption with liftoff starting in SDO AIA 304 around 2024-09-10T09:51Z with dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and opening field lines in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is visible on the limb from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-10T20:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a far sided filament eruption and resulting field line movement seen off the South limb in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-10T23:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is wide opening field lines seen along the West limb in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 beginning at approx. 10/22:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2. There is currently no SOHO LASCO imagery for this event due to a data gap from 11/02:36Z to 11/07:12Z. The source of this event is an M1.0 class flare peaking at 2024-09-10T23:50Z and subsequent eruption from AR 3814 (N16W03) as seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 304. The flare peaked at 2024-09-10T23:50Z, however the eruption continued through approx. 11/01:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 304. Opening field lines, slight dimming and a possible EUV wave can be seen propagating towards the NE in SDO AIA 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195. Due to the lack of SOHO data available to triangulate the source, there is some degree of uncertainty in the latitude and longitude of this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint and relatively narrow CME seen to the West in STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source is brightening and slowly opening field lines from a bright region beyond the SW limb, located at about S10W115 as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195/304 imagery starting at 2024-09-11T12:15Z. Opening field lines from just beyond the limb as seen from SDO, can be seen spanning N00 to S20, starting at 2024-09-11T12:02Z in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint yet fast CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-11T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to a data gap from 2024-09-11T14:38Z to 2024-09-11T22:23Z. The source of this event is an M1.8 class flare peaking at 2024-09-11T15:30Z and a subsequent fast eruption of material seen along the Eastern limb (approx. S20E90). The flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 131, along with material seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-11T19:48Z, as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. Possible source of this event is an M1.6 class flare from the vicinity of AR 3811 (S15W80) peaking at 2024-09-11T17:26Z, as seen in SDO AIA 131. There is also a lot of general field line movement and brightening off of the West limb seen in SDO AIA 171 at this time, that may also contribute to the eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-12T00:36Z. The source of this CME is likely an M5.0 class flare from AR 3811 (S13W78). This CME is quite faint, and the front dissipates quickly.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-12T19:48Z and C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a C9.7 flare and subsequent eruption from near the East limb (S18E80) as seen in SDO AIA 131, 304 and STEREO A EUVI 304 beginning at approximately 12/18:48Z. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195. This event is only seen in one frame of STEREO A imagery due to a data gap from 12/19:23Z to 12/22:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright, lightbulb CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-12T21:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is clear rising loops and opening field lines seen off of the NE limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright wide CME off the southwest limb, likely associated with the M1.2 flare from AR 3811 (S13W91) peaking at 2024-0913T00:00Z. Coronal signatures include a large ejecta seen in AIA 131 and in SUVI 284 starting at 2024-0913T00:27Z and a wide opening of field lines on/behind the limb in SUVI 284 starting at 2024-0913T01:24Z. High-rising post-eruptive arcades are seen in AIA 193 on limb (and less prominently a few more southward on the disk).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, directly following CME: 2024-09-13T02:00Z in the field of view of the coronagraphs. The potential source is from the cluster of Active Regions in the southwest, with field line movement visible in STEREO A EUV 195 and SDO AIA 193 around 2024-09-13T04:35Z. Post-eruptive loops are visible for several hours following the eruption in SDO AIA 131, 171, and 193. Outflowing material is visible in the coronagraphs following this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a clear front in the northwest in SOHO and north in STEREO A COR2, indicating its directedness towards STEREO A and a bit north. Likely source is is unspecified flaring south of AR 3814 (N12W33) around 2024-09-13T08:24Z, with a medium-sized dimming and post-eruptive arcades as coronal signatures. This eruption is right at the disk center in STEREO A EUV imagery. In EUVI A 304 we also see a small ejecta directed southwards. The flaring is unspecified because it coincides with a much more intense flaring from Active Region 3823 on southwest limb, so the intensity of this lesser flare cannot be measured.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source location in available EUV imagery is unclear, and the CME may be farsided. The CME is obscured by a data gap in real-time in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 from 2024-09-13T13:48Z-15:12Z and in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-09-13T15:53Z-18:09Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The start time is in SOHO LASCO C2 after a data gap from 2024-09-13T13:48Z-15:12Z. The potential source is opening field lines and brightening loops seen on the west limb in SDO AIA 193. The activity starts around 2024-09-13T09:00Z and continues for several hours following the eruption. The activity is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV imagery. Overlapping CMEs are visible in the coronagraphs around this time, and may also be from this activity to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source location is likely field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171/193 on the west limb starting at 2024-09-13T15:28Z. Rising loops can also be seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear, and the CME is likely backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2A seemingly from an eruption near S15E75 just below AR 3285 as evidenced by the appearance of narrow ejecta seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, and 193.

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-09-14T17:38Z-22:38Z. There is no clear source visible for this CME in available EUV imagery.

There is no STEREO A COR2 data available for this due to a data gap from 2024-09-14T17:38Z to 2024-09-14T22:38Z. There is no clear source seen on the disk, however some faint field line movement is visible in SDO AIA 171, but it's difficult to tell if it's front sided or far sided movement.

note: Faint, narrow CME visible to the S/SE in SOHO imagery (SOHO imagery flips after midnight zulu, start time of CME based on first appearance in SOHO C2 in unrotated image) and to the S/SW in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears as moving/opening field lines along the southern limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-09-17T15:47Z.

This CME does not have a distinct leading edge and significantly widens as it progresses.

note: Faint loop CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-18T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. note: Bright CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-18T12:36Z, as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this CME is an eruption on or just beyond the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193. Field line opening is visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195, as well as post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131. The source is a long and narrow horizontal area of very gradual dimming and gradual field line movement seen centered at N50 and stretching from E20 to W70 in SDO AIA 193 / 171. It is difficult to pin down an exact start time for the field line movement at this area on the disk, but best estimate is 2024-09-19T04:54Z as seen in SDO AIA 193, with dimming becoming more clear by 07:50Z. Subtle field line movement can be seen on the NW limb starting as early as 2024-09-19T05:48Z in SDO AIA 171/193. GOES SUVI instruments were in an eclipse at and around these timestamps.

The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event. Faint field line movement may be visible beyond the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 imagery starting around 2024-09-19T21:40Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, and GOES SUVI 284 along with post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131. This filament appears to deflect towards the SW as it progresses as seen in GOES SUVI 304. A faint EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193 also appears to expand more to the west.

The eruption is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195. While the filament does not clearly deflect in EUV imagery, this is the most likely candidate source for this CME based on event timing and location.

There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery from 2024-10-02T14:08Z to 2024-10-02T17:08Z, in addition to being in campaign mode for the Parker Solar Probe perihelion pass which affects COR2A image quality and cadence.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-03T08:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption centered at approx. N25E70 with liftoff beginning at approx. 2024-10-03T07:30Z as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This filament erupted gradually, so there is a small amount of material seen preceding the main bulk of the CME from which the measurement was based.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2020-10-03T09:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption beginning at approx. 2024-10-03T09:19Z centered at approx. S30W15 with Southern deflection as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Full halo CME observed in SOHO LASCO, and full halo directed slightly more eastward in STEREO COR2A. The source is an X9.0 flare from AR 3842 observed in many wavelengths but mainly SDO AIA 131, starting at 2024-10-03T12:08Z and peaking at T12:18Z. Also observed as an EUV wave and dimming in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284, with surface brightening in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the NW within the outflow of the halo CME: 2024-10-03T12:48Z associated with a filament eruption lifting off near N25W52 or so seen best in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI 304. The CME is not seen in STEREO A well, due to poor image quality and a data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Large loop CME seen to the NE in SOHO/STEREO A embedded in outflow of halo CME: 2024-10-03T12:48Z. Associated with a filament eruption/snapping of magnetic field lines and surge seen best in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 171 near N30E60; the signature in SDO AIA 171 is particularly clear, as there is widely opening field line movement off the northeast limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME with an auriform presentation in both the outline of its bulk and shock, seen to the west in SOHO. Associated with a strong eruption from AR 13844 near S10W50 following an M6.7-class flare; an EUV wave is seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-03T22:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this CME is a minor filament eruption beginning at approximately 03/20:30Z centered at N35E50 as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 304, although the CME itself appears to be deflected towards the North. Minor field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193 as a result of this eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-03T23:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this eruption, however faint field line movement can be seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approximately 03/22:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and to the south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be two eruptions in close proximity to each other in the SW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk. A dimming region possibly associated with a faint filament eruption is visible in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 2024-10-04T02:00Z in the SW near ARs 13842, 13839, and 13844 followed by moving/opening field lines visible in SDO/AIA 171 starting around 2024-10-04T03:00Z in the SW below ARs 13844, 13843, and 13836. The moving/opening field lines are largely visible heading to the west while the dimming appears to have some southern directionality. A third separate eruption from AR 13842 (an M4.0 flare) is likely associated with an overlapping CME feature. There is some uncertainty with this analysis due to the multiple eruptions in close proximity and timing to when the CME is first visible in coronagraph imagery. Both SOHO and STEREO A coronagraphs have data gaps during this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A southern CME with a somewhat uncertain front seen with some uncertainty overlapping with the earlier 2024-10-04T04:13Z CME and discernible mostly in difference imagery (not clearly seen in white light images). It is likely associated with the M4.0 flare from Active Region 3842 and the associated narrow, south-directed ejecta seen in AIA/SUVI 304 starting at 2024-10-04T05:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-04T06:24Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this CME is a very minor eruption from AR 3838 (N1W52) beginning at approx. 04/05:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 193, although the CME is likely slightly deflected Northward. Minor field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-04T10:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this CME is field line movement seen in the vicinity of S35W30 beginning at approximately 04/09:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-04T13:25Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption from the vicinity of AR 3844 (S15W37) beginning at approximately 04/12:30Z, although the CME itself appears to exhibit Southern deflection. Field line opening can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 171 along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A wide CME directly north in STEREO A coronagraph and a bit towards NNE in SOHO. There is a wider shock and a narrower brighter bulk. The shock looks like an asymmetric halo with additional part seen to the west in COR2A. There was no source found on the Earth-facing disk so the CME is likely backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very diffuse front with many follow up emission. The source may be a broad field line movement over the NW limb beginning as early as 2024-10-04T23Z but the source is unclear.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint front only seen in running difference imagery from SOHO (C2 and C3), but not discernible in the white light SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 imagery (which is sparse and low quality because of the currently STEREO campaign). No definitive source has been found for this CME. This front is followed by multiple similar faint fronts.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A very faint and narrow outflow to the south and southwest.  The source has not been found - but there is a lot of activity in the SW quadrant which may be obscuring the source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain, with no one distinct eruptive source and the entire southwest quadrant of SDO AIA 171 imagery observing broad field line movement from as early as 4Z this morning, likely due to the numerous active regions in the SW and SW limb.

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and in STEREO COR2A white light imagery. The source is a thin jet-like filament eruption from on or just beyond the SW limb, best observed erupting at 2024-10-05T11:52Z in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint front - one of multiple faint fronts today - that is mainly seen in difference imagery and has no clear source in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME to the northwest. Its source is likely the inconspicuous  opening of field lines in the northwest behind the limb seen in AIA 193/171 after 2024-10-05T19:05Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-06T04:48Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, however some very minor field line opening can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 at approx. 06/04:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-06T06:12Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-10-07T03:48Z. Also seen in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is like some activity from the vicinity of AR 3841. There is some minor brightening and movement along field lines best seen in SDO AIA 171 starting about 1.5 hours prior to the CME appearing in C2.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Wide, bright CME seen to the southwest in SOHO C2/C3 seemingly composed of two or more overlapping loops with internal structure clearly visible and no cavity. Presence of very faint shock may possibly be seen due south in LASCO C2 running difference imagery and may begin to reveal itself to the north-northeast in late SOHO frames after 22:30Z, though disjoint from the main CME body. Associated with a sympathetic eruption resulting from the long duration X2.1/X1.0-class flares (AR3842) located farther behind the southwestern limb than where the X2.1 takes place (W60) as seen in SDO AIA 171 imagery; the CME appears to originate closer to the southwestern limb. Fast, widely opening field lines are also observed in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery for a few frames prior to a data gap starting at 2024-10-08T03:38Z. The source may be related to field line movement visible near the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery around 2024-10-08T00:40Z. Additionally, there are rising loops/possible post-eruptive arcades visible near the western limb around 01:00Z in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 imagery which may also be related to this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is visible in STEREO A COR2 for a few frames prior to a data gap beginning at 2024-10-08T03:38Z. The source is likely related to an eruption near S19W72 starting around 2024-10-08T01:54Z seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, and is only visible in STEREO A COR2 after the leading edge is out of the field of view due to a data gap from 2024-10-08T03:38Z to 09:23Z. The source is a large filament eruption centered near S25W30 which begins to erupt, deflecting southward, around 2024-10-08T05:20Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at the time of the eruption, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 06:30Z in SDO AIA131, 171, and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and a few frames of STEREO A COR2 prior to a data gap starting at 2024-10-08T13:23Z. The source is likely far-sided, and seen as faint opening of field lines visible beyond the eastern limb in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2024-10-08T11:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Relatively narrow CME first seen in the East initially by STEREO A COR2, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. This event gets quickly overtaken by the X1.8-flare-associated halo 2024-10-09T02:12Z CME. The source of this event is possibly a more minor flare sympathetic to the X flare happening at the same time in Active Region 3853 (N20E63) with post-eruptive arcades or more minor opening field lines and slight dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284 originating from the vicinity of AR 3852 (S14E53). This more minor flare is not measurable since it coincides with the more intense flare.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, fast and complex-shaped full halo CME associated with the X1.8 class flare from the Active Region 13848 (N13W08). The CME has two lobes or fronts: the more western, slightly earlier one, and the more central on to the northeast. The flare is associated with the significant eruption marked by an EUV wave, a large area of deep dimming and by bright post-eruptive arcades. There also  seems to be a second eruption - the initially slowly developing eruption of a very large filament spanning from N20W15 to N15W55, to the northwest of the Active Region 3848, which starts prior to the X flare (~2024-10-08T22:19Z). This earlier eruption may be responsible for the more western lobe or front of this CME (which could possibly be a separate CME). The X-class flare could be potentially be responsible for the more central, northeastern lobe/front of this complex event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A clear, more western loop especially well seen in SOHO C2 (starting at 2024-10-09T02:12Z) and overlapping with a more central front associated with the Xclass flare. The start time was set to 02:23Z to distinguish it from the more central CME. The source of this more western front is likely the initially slowly developing eruption of a very large filament spanning from N20W15 to N15W55 to the northwest of Active Region 3848 which started prior to the X flare (~2024-10-08T22:19Z). This earlier eruption may be responsible for the more western lobe/front, while the flare could be responsible for the more central, northeastern front of this complex CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and a few frames of STEREO A COR2 after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 lasting from 2024-10-09T13:53Z to 2024-10-09T18:53Z. This CME is associated with the X1.4 flare from AR 13842 (S10W85) close to the SW limb. There is a narrow stream of ejecta visible in GOES SUVI 304 sourced from AR 13842 but deflected to the north and off the limb. In GOES SUVI 284, wide and fast opening field lines and departure of plasma from the W limb is visible. Very limited SDO AIA imagery for this event due to a shutter maneuver.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

S02W90 exhibiting Northern deflection) beginning at approx. 11/12:08Z as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304.
