note: Streamer blowout CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The exact source is not clear, but may be associated with moving/opening field lines in the NE of SDO/AIA 171 and 193 starting around 2024-10-14T09:30Z. The front of this CME is very diffuse, but a later front that was more defined was used for the analysis of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-14T14:36Z, although this event likely began sooner but was not visible due to the cadence of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. The source of this CME is an M1.8 class flare from AR 3848 (N17W86) peaking at 14/13:37Z. This flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 131 along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. It overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-10-14T20:36Z. The source can be seen as brightening seen near AR 3848 just beyond the west limb. Field line movement is also seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-10-14T17:36Z. The source is likely on the west limb, and some possible post-eruption brightening visible at 2024-10-14T21:27Z in SDO/AIA 304 near AR 3848.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the S in C2, C3 and to the SW in COR2A. There is no discernable source in UV imagery found. This CME is likely far-sided, based on the lack of source on the Earth-facing disk and when comparing the position of the CME in SOHO LASCO to STEREO A COR2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible in the SE of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely the liftoff of filamentary material from a long filament stretching along the S/SE limb, seen in SDO AIA 304 around 2024-10-15T01:24Z. There appears to be recurring partial eruptions from this filament, so there may be additional fronts seen at later times from this same source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the NW in STEREO A COR2. Not visible in real-time in SOHO LASCO imagery due to a data gap from approximately 2024-10-15T08:30Z-22:15Z. The potential source is some faint field line movement best seen beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUV 195 at 2024-10-15T10:25Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first visible in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-10-15T22:06Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The start time of this CME is delayed due to data gaps in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 (15/07:48Z to 15/21:26Z) and STEREO A COR2 (15/13:23Z to 15/23:09Z). The source is associated with the M1.7 flare peaking at 2024-10-15T18:18Z from AR 3848 on the NW limb, around N19W90. Opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2024-10-15T18:13Z. The eruption is not visible in STEREO A EUVI 195 due to a data gap in real-time from 2024-10-15T13:25Z-22:55Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-15T23:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of thus CME is a small eruption seen on NW Limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-10-15T21:37Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field line movement visible near or slightly beyond the northwest limb in SDO AIA 193 imagery starting around 2024-10-16T00:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field line movement visible near or slightly beyond the northwest limb in SDO AIA 193 imagery starting around 2024-10-16T03:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field line movement visible beyond the northwest limb in SDO AIA 193 imagery starting around 2024-10-16T07:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a far-sided halo, primarily directed towards the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and northwest in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely far-sided as an opening of field lines is visible beyond the northeast limb starting around 2024-10-16T22:10Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery. The source may originate from former Active Region 13841, which was located around longitude -163 at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide loop to the southwest with many consecutive fronts which overlaps with the far-sided halo 2024-10-16T23:12Z CME. The source is likely a faint slow opening field lines seen far beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 284 and in EUVI A 195, starting as early as 2024-10-16T22:50Z and lasting until about 2024-10-17T04:50Z. There is a faint opening of field lines and there appears to be a rising loop departing as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A moderately narrow CME to the northeast preceding the wider CME: 2024-10-17T08:36Z. Its source could be a part of the erupting filament seen in SDO AIA imagery spanning from N30E10 to N40E50. The movement and gradual liftoff of the filamentary material can be seen in SDO AIA 304/171/193 and GOES SUVI 304/284 starting ~2024-10-17T06:00Z-07:30Z. This eruption is possibly the source of both CME:2024-10-17T07:36Z and CME:2024-10-17T08:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A loop like CME to the northeast following a narrower 2024-10-17T07:36Z CME. The source could be the filament eruption seen in SDO AIA imagery spanning from about N30E10 to N40E50. Movement and liftoff of the filamentary material can be seen in SDO AIA 304/171/193 and GOES SUVI 304/284 lasting from about 2024-10-17T06:00Z-07:30Z, so this may be the source of both CME:2024-10-17T07:36Z and CME:2024-10-17T08:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like, narrow CME seen out to a few solar radii first at 2024-10-17T23:12Z to the east after SOHO and STEREO A data refilled but the start time is earlier than this; possibly associated with a minor eruption near or just beyond the eastern limb as seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 with northward deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a fuzzy front, preceded and followed by outflows and following the slow/faint 2024-10-18T06:12Z CME. The start time of this event can be a bit earlier. The source is possibly a very minor faint eruption with ejecta/movement of field lines seen on/behind the NW limb in AIA 193/171 starting at 2024-10-18T11:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint diffuse CME to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3 (barely visible), and possibly STEREO A COR2 imagery (unclear if feature seen to the west in STA is outflow or this CME). This CME is likely associated with the M6.5 flare from AR13854 (S03W82) peaking at 2024-10-19T06:56Z best seen in SDO/AIA 131. A filament to the north of the AR begins to erupt around 2024-10-19T06:24Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304 and appears to lift off with the flare and may be associated with this CME as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: This CME is visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be an eruption from AR 3863 starting around 2024-10-19T09:00Z in SDO/AIA 304/171/211/94. Moving/opening field lines are visible in the SE of SDO/AIA 171, however it is not clear if these moving/opening field lines are associated with this eruption or another eruption that may be associated with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-10-19T09:48Z to the SE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME to the south. A potential source could be the opening of field lines to the S/SE in SDO/AIA 171 around 2024-10-19T09Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow faint CME with a dimpled front. The likely source is a minor movement of field line behind the northwest limb at latitude ~20 seen starting around 2024-10-19T17:40Z in AIA 193/171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint CME to the southeast, becoming wider with time, consisting of a faint shock on its sides. The source for this eruption appears to be movement/opening of field lines just behind the SE limb (lat ~-20) seen around 2024-10-19T22:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like CME seen to the east-northeast predominantly in SOHO C2 imagery, but also in C3 imagery and STEREO A COR2; it appears with much more contrast in running difference imagery as opposed to white light imagery. Likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity as evidenced by triangulation, although a possible very low confidence source could be the post eruptive arcades on the earth facing disk around N27E70.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright loop CME seen to the southeast in SOHO and STEREO A imagery, associated with a significant field line movement behind the southeastern limb as seen best in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet CME seen to the northeast in SOHO C2 imagery shortly after the wide and bright 2024-20-21T09:24Z CME seen to the southeast, possibly overlapping. No major source eruptions were found for this CME, but the CME may be associated with a magnetic field line breaking off the eastern limb best seen in SDO AIA 193 observed near 2024-10-21T11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: New CME embedded in the outflow in the CME: 2024-10-21T09:24Z seen to the southeast associated with a secondary, sympathetic eruption taking place off the southeast limb following the 2024-10-21T08:00Z opening field lines characterized by new opening field lines seen best in GOES SUVI 284 off the southeast limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The start time was difficult to determine as this event overlaps with preceding CME: 2024-10-21T13:48Z and CME: 2024-10-21T09:24Z. The source is likely far-sided and related to an opening of field lines and eruption visible beyond the southeast limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 and 304 imagery starting around 2024-10-21T14:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the north in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is visible after a data gap in C2. The source is not clear but may possibly be associated with an eruption near N07E00 starting around 2024-10-22T04:44Z. This eruption is best seen in SDO/AIA 131, 304, and 193. There is possibly deflection to the north due to a coronal hole due south of the source eruption location.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Source is one of several instances of narrowly opening field lines and ejecta from either on or just beyond the E limb at latitude N00, but with northern deflection. Instances start as early as 2024-10-22T03:41Z (very diffuse outflow associated with that instance). There is a clearer instance of ejecta seen at 2024-10-22T07:30Z, which may possibly be the source for this CME, though the timing is rather early. It's also possible the source for this particular front is sourced from even further beyond the limb than we can see in UV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fan-shaped CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. The source appears to lie on or just beyond the SE limb, observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as rapidly moving field lines starting around 2024-10-22T17:01Z, and further evidenced on the far-side around E95 by triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the W/SW in all coronagraphs, but not until later frames of STEREO COR2A due to a data gap spanning 2024-10-22T13:38Z-T19:38Z. This CME has a wide fan-shaped front extending further to the southward direction in coronagraph imagery, with the brightest bulk and nose more in the ecliptic. The main source is a brightening between ARs 3860/3859 centered around S05W61, observed in SDO AIA 131 alongside field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193 and some surface brightening in SDO AIA 304, beginning around 2024-10-22T17:04Z. A small filament just to the NE, centered around N03W48, erupts simultaneously in SDO AIA 304 with this (starting slowly around 2024-10-22T16:41Z) and may contribute to the front despite the offset in location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint flux rope CME, which is also a streamer blowout, seen to the south in STEREO A COR2 and south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There are initially two overlapping fronts seen in early C2 and early COR2A coronagraph imagery: a faint flux rope loop and a more narrow hollow loop which at first appears to travel faster, but by the time both fronts reach the edge of the C2 FOV, both fronts appear to travel as one. No clear source is seen on disk in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. The source of this CME appears to be filament ejecta seen near S17E80 in SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2024-10-23T10:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the north-northeast in SOHO LASCO and northeast in STEREO A COR2 that appears to be associated with a minor eruption with northward deflection occurring near N19E15 south of Active Region 3864 as seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284. Flickering magnetic field lines are observed off the northeast limb nearly simultaneously after the on-disk signature seen in SDO AIA 171 which may suggest, with low confidence, a possible simultaneous far-side component. Triangulation of the CME using SOHO/STEREO A coronagraphs suggested with higher confidence that the CME was predominantly associated with the on-disk signatures.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint and fast loop seen to the southeast as defined by its brighter leading edge similar in appearance to the 2024-10-23T11:12Z CME; no definitive source for this CME was found, but could be associated with moving field lines off the southeast limb as seen best in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow, faint CME observed to the southeast in STEREO A COR2 first during a SOHO data gap at which point SOHO later backfilled. Likely associated with diverging field lines seen off the southeast limb beginning around 14:45Z but becoming more apparent by 16:00Z best in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an X3.3 flare starting at 2024-10-24T03:30Z from AR 3869 (approx. S17E68). Brightening and post eruptive arcades are observed in SDO AIA 131/171/193/335, EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is also seen from STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source may be activity from AR 3869, as opening field lines can be seen in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-10-24T09:00Z. The CME is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-24T11:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen for this event, leading to the conclusion that the source is likely beyond the Eastern limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-24T11:36Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is some very minor field line movement seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-24T12:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this eruption is some minor field line movement seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T13:48Z. In real-time, there was no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 white light imagery available due to a data outage beginning at 2024-10-24T12:48Z that resolved and backfilled on 2024-10-25. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this CME is a small area of field line movement along the SE limb (approx. S40E90) as seen in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow jet CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T14:36Z. In real-time, there was no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 white light imagery available due to a data outage beginning at 2024-10-24T12:48Z that resolved and backfilled on 2024-10-25. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this event is a small eruption along the East limb (approx. S02E85) as seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T16:12Z. In real-time, there was no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 white light imagery available due to a data outage beginning at 2024-10-24T12:48Z that resolved and backfilled on 2024-10-25. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this CME is some faint field line movement seen beyond the East limb in SDO AIA 171. This source seems to be obscured by the brightening of an active region which has just rotated onto the disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T18:48Z. In real-time, there was no SOHO LASCO C2/C3 white light imagery available due to a data outage beginning at 2024-10-24T12:48Z that resolved and backfilled on 2024-10-25. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this event is a narrow eruption of material seen along the East limb (approx. S11E85) exhibiting Northern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source may be activity from a cluster of ARs in the southeast, including potential eruption activity from AR 3872, as opening field lines are seen around 2024-10-25T02:00Z near the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 in ISWA.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The source is an M1.1 flare peaking at 2024-10-25T07:33Z from AR 3873 (approx. S10E72) as seen in SDO AIA 131. The eruption is best seen in GOES SUVI 304. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304. In real-time, SOHO data was unavailable starting around 2024-10-24T12:48Z, but later backfilled.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source can be seen as an ejecta of material near AR 3873, best seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-10-25T08:37Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and faintly visible in STEREO A COR2. The potential source can be seen around N10 near the limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-10-25T12:17Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely an eruption from AR 3873, near S10E70. An eruption can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-10-25T14:49Z from AR 3873, and there is another eruption preceding it starting at 2024-10-25T12:41Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and (slightly brighter in) STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME and only a few frames available in STEREO A COR2 imagery before the nightly data gap in real-time imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like CME to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. No STEREO A COR2 imagery available during this CME due to nightly data gap in real-time imagery. There is no clear source for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint jet-like CME to the S in SOHO LASCO C2, C3. Data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source appears to be small eruption from AR3865 (S22E00) which is heavily deflected south with some southeast directionality.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo directed towards the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an eruption which is associated with an M9.5 flare from Active Region 13873 (S14E56) and X1.8 flare from Active Region 13873 (S16E60) starting around 2024-10-26T06:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A wide opening of field lines is visible over the southeast limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193, with post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 starting around 07:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME seen to the south-southeast in the outflow of the halo CME 2024-10-26T06:48Z. May be associated with a secondary eruption or outflow near S35E60.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow yet bright CME seen best in SOHO C2 nearly due west along the outflow of several more minor CMEs to the southwest. Likely associated with eruptive activity just behind the western limb as evidenced by opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-10-26T07:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME/outflow in the wake of the earlier significant 2024-10-26T06:48Z CME. Its source is not clear but there is some movement in the filament eruption in the SE preceding this time.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet CME seen to the south-southeast in STEREO A COR2. Unclear source. May potentially be associated with eruptive activity from the southeast, including the recently eruptive Active Region 3872 with strong southward deflection. note: Faint, near partial halo CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-31T13:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is brightening and a subsequent eruption from Active Region 3877 (S16E02) beginning at approx. 31/12:51Z. The brightening is visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with the eruptive material visible in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, and wide but faint field line movement seen South of the Active Region in SDO AIA 193. This flare brightened in tandem with AR 3875, however AR 3875 was responsible for the majority of the brightening and is there for the associated Active Region for the event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-31T14:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a large, slow filament eruption along the Southern limb as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. This filament began to erupt at approximately 31/05:00Z, but appeared to hover just above the limb before fully erupting into the corona beginning at approximately 31/12:00Z.

instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the NW in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2024-11-06T20:23Z after a data gap. The CME is about half way through the FOV of STEREO A COR2 in the first available image. CME is also visible to the NW in LASCO C2/C3; however, after the resumption of data for the SOHO downlink period starting at 2024-11-06T20:55Z, the leading edge of the CME has already passed out of the FOV of C2. There are a couple of possibilities for the source of this CME; however, the source most likely far-sided based on measurements. There is some faint field line movement best seen in GOES SUVI 284 from well beyond the NW limb a couple hours prior to the CME first becoming visible in STEREO A COR2. The measurement of the CME indicates that former AR 3875, which rotated off the Earth-facing disk on 2024-11-04, could be a good source candidate.

The filament is centered at ~N20E25 and stretches from N27E40 to N17E17. Coronal signatures of this CME include an ejecta seen erupting in SDO AIA 304 and a dimming and post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 193/195.

Some filament material lands on the Earth-facing disk post-eruption, evidenced by spots of brightening on the disk in SDO AIA 304, so a range of longitudes may exist for this CME source, but nonetheless is it far-north and out of the ecliptic.

The flare can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 94 and 131, and the filament can be seen in SDO AIA, STEREO A COR2 and GOES SUVI 304. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A coronagraph imagery. No source for this CME was found on the Earth-facing disk, so the CME is likely to be farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-18T03:24Z. Also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely a small area of dimming best seen in SDO AIA 193 just to the W of AR 3901 starting at 2024-11-18T02:45Z that is accompanied by some faint field line movement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-18T04:36Z. CME also visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely a small area of brightening near AR 3900 and some associated faint field line movement on the NE limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting at ~2024-11-18T03:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-18T12:12Z. Also seen to SW in SOHO LASCO C3. CME occurs during a data gap in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely an M1.6 flare from AR 3897 that peaked at 11:12Z. The flare and associated eruption can be seen in SDO AIA 304 starting at 2024-11-18T11:09Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-11-18T15:38Z. The source is likely an M2.0 flare and eruption from Active Region 13901 (S10E74) starting around 2024-11-18T19:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the east limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery, with post-eruptive arcades starting to form around 2024-11-18T20:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor, puff-like CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. There are few candidates for a source region on the Earth facing disk in available EUV imagery and appears to fit a far-sided leading edge measurement using triangulation, so the eruption is likely far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very minor eruption seen to the east-southeast in all available coronagraph imagery which may be associated with a small point-source eruption occurring from near AR 3901 near S10E75 or so; some field line movement is seen off the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the high NW in all coronagraphs, with STEREO COR2A returning from a data gap at 2024-11-20T00:09Z and barely catching the CME front before it leaves its FOV. This CME erupted very slowly at first with speeds around 63 km/s, accelerating to a more constant speed by ~2024-11-20T23:00Z well into LASCO C3's FOV. The source is far northern latitude field line movement on or beyond the NW limb, observed best in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 beginning around 2024-11-19T08:00Z and accelerating faster around 2024-11-19T12:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to data gap lasting from 2024-11-19T12:38Z to 2024-11-20T00:23Z. Source is opening field lines near AR 13892 (S10W89) on the SW limb. Seen in GOES SUVI 284/304 at 2024-11-19T16:37Z. Field line movement on the SW limb near AR 13892 also seen in SDO AIA 193/171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to field line movement starting around 2024-11-20T04:30Z visible over the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint but visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is too faint to be considered measurable in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to field line movement visible on or just beyond the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-20T08:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-11-20T13:38Z. The source is related to an M1.1 flare and subsequent eruption from Active Region 13897 (S08W89) starting around 2024-11-20T19:15Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An opening of field lines is visible over the western limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-11-20T13:38Z. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the southeast, where the likely source a small filament eruption near the Active Region 13899 (S18E26). The filament stretches from S13E11 to S25E50 and lifts off starting around 2024-11-21T01:00Z, as seen in SDO AIA 131, 193, 304 imagery. There is also a movement of field lines in SDO AIA 171 which seems to be closer to the limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright wide CME to the southeast, with a wider, more halo-like shock front seen in SOHO. Except for two early timestamps, the CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A. Its source is a significant eruption of a large filament off the southeast limb (likely behind the limb), seen most clearly in AIA 304, 171 and SUVI 304 (but also seen in other channels) starting with 2024-11-21T11:17Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright and fast partial halo to the northwest, with bulk and (fainter) shock fronts, associated with the fast backsided eruption marked by an EUV wave and fast opening of field lines behind the NW limb seen around 2024-11-21T18Z. The source is backsided, based on the coronal signatures and might be Active Region 3889 which would be at the longitude 115 to 120 degrees at the moment.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Slow to erupt CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery but speeds up in later frames. This CME appears to be associated with a filament eruption along the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-11-21T19:45Z. There are also moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be an eruption in the NE between N25E35 to N35E50 associated with moving/opening field lines in SDO/AIA 171, dimming in SDO/AIA 193, and brightening in SDO/AIA 131 between 21:00Z and 22:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain with no visible source in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI, or STEREO A EUVI. The CME is less visible in SOHO LASCO C2, becoming more distinct in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-11-22T04:17Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this CME is some minor field line movement and dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 at approx. 22/03:27Z centered near S40E70.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, faint CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-11-22T07:12Z as well as by SOHO LASCO CC3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from the East limb (approx. S20E90) beginning at approx. 22/06:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 304. Field line movement is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-11-22T08:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption beginning at approx. 22/08:25Z centered at approx. S30E20 exhibiting heavy Eastern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 304. Faint field line movement is also visible in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Far SSW thin CME seen in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain with no visible source in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI, or STEREO A EUVI. The CME is less visible in SOHO LASCO C2, becoming more distinct in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first visible in the West by STEREO A COR 2 beginning at 2024-11-22T09:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. There is no clear source seen for this CME, and the leading edge fades quickly in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

The source of this event is a region of dimming centered at approx. N35E35 as seen in SDO AIA 211, along with opening field lines seen in SDO AIA 171 tracing back to this same region.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The source may be an eruption from AR 3906 starting around 2024-11-22T15:00Z, best seen in SDO/AIA 304 (filament ejecta), SDO/AIA 171 (moving/opening field lines), and SDO/AIA 193 (moving/opening field lines and brightening).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Mystery faint front to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 difference imagery starting around 18:48Z. The source is unclear but may possibly be associated with very slow moving/opening field lines along the southern limb in SDO/AIA 171. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The CME is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The source is likely an M1.0 flare from AR 3906 (S18E74) peaking at 2024-11-22T22:15Z, with brightening and an eruption best seen in SDO AIA 193. Opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is not clearly visible in STEREO A EUV 195 due to a data gap from approx. 2024-11-22T12:35Z-22:05Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is an eruption around N25E30 starting around 2024-11-22T19:45Z, best seen as dimming in SDO AIA 193. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely beyond the west limb of the Earth facing disk, as moving/opening field lines can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting at 2024-11-23T00:00Z. The eruption is best seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195, where opening field lines from an AR near the limb are visible between a data gap from 2024-11-22T23:05Z to 2024-11-23T00:25Z.

note: Narrow CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is an eruption near the west limb from the point of view of STEREO A EUVI 195 starting 2024-11-23T01:25Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171/193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Two potential source candidate eruptions are seen in EUV imagery: one around S15W55 (near AR 3898) and another around S25W55 starting around 2024-11-23T03:38Z, best seen in SDO AIA 193. The eruption near AR 3898 is believed to be the more likely candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, narrow CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear, and may be eruptive activity from AR 3906.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source may be an eruption on the disk from AR 3906 (S16E65) starting at 2024-11-23T09:37Z, based on field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME faintly visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. It is obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The potential source may be an eruption on the disk starting around 2024-11-23T12:01Z around S15E50, best seen with some brightening and rising field lines in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO AIA 171.

note: Faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap. The source appears to be an eruption from AR 13898/plage region 13893 in the SW based on SDO/AIA 131 and 193 starting around 2024-11-23T19:20Z. There are also moving/opening field lines visible along the limb in GOES SUVI 284 which may be associated with the eruption on the disk but could also indicate a far sided simultaneous eruption which could play into overlapping fronts seen with this CME to the SW.

note: Narrow CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-11-24T10:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no distinct source for this CME, however a large amount of field line movement, brightening and general activity is visible in the vicinity of ARs 3905 (S09E48) and 3906 (S16E54) as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-11-24T16:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not reliably visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is a minor eruption and brightening centered at approx. N15E75 as seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, jet-like CME first visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-25T00:24Z. Also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not visible in STEREO A COR2. There appears to be some northward deflection starting a couple frames into the propagation. There is not a definitive source for this CME. One possibility is some brightening and activity just to the NW of AR 3905 best seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at 00:08Z. This coronal signature is likely too late to be the source. Another more likely source possibility is some faint field line movement on the ESE limb best seen in SDO AIA 171 starting at 2024-11-24T23:21Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-25T01:48Z. CME also seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is very faint in white light and is better seen in running difference imagery. The source of this CME is possibly some minor brightening and movement of plasma centered around N20E25 starting around 2024-11-25T00:27Z with some northward deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-25T03:12Z. CME also seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely a small filament eruption centered around S40-45E28 that is visible in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 193 starting about 2024-11-25T01:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

This CME closely follows CME: 2024-11-25T03:12Z but is slightly slower and slightly wider and is clearly distinguishable in running difference imagery. There is not a clearly definitive source for this CME, but a possible candidate is a deflected source associated with an M1.1 flare from AR 3906 (S13E46) that peaked at 2024-11-25T01:59Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME. The front appears to be faint with a brighter core and possible h-alpha emission visible in C2 imagery. The source appears to be a filament eruption starting around 17Z beyond the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304. Associated moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 as well as in GOES SUVI 284 imagery
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-11-25T13:38Z to 2024-11-26T00:38Z. This CME partially overlaps with and follows in the path of preceding CME: 2024-11-25T18:00Z. The source for this event is unknown and likely far-sided, but may be related to the filament eruption visible just beyond the southwest limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-25T17:00Z, which was associated with the aforementioned CME: 2024-11-25T18:00Z.

There is not a clear, separate source for this CME, and it follows in a similar propagation path to CME: 2024-11-25T18:00Z and CME: 2024-11-25T19:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and possibly to the SE in STEREO A COR2 imagery following a data gap. The CME is likely associated with the M1.9 flare from AR 13091 as seen from SDO/AIA 131 and associated dimming in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 20:33Z. The dimming and associated EUV wave is seen moving out in all directions, most notably seen to the north, east, and south of the source location. This CME event overlaps with CMEs visible to the southwest which began around 2024-11-25T18:00Z.

note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-25T21:36Z. CME also seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 (partially obscured by pylon) and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely some activity involving ARs 3905 and 3906 staring around 2025-11-25T17:00Z that continues for a few hours. The movement and brightening is particularly visible in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 193.

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is limited imagery available for this CME in STEREO A COR2 data. The source appears to be a filament eruption on the eastern limb of SDO/AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-11-26T12:50Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 284 to the east with this eruption.

note: Narrow CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to the faintness of the CME. Source is a C3.5 flare from S20W72 (no AR) with peak time 2024-11-27T02:28Z and a narrow ribbon of ejecta similarly from about S20 near the SW limb seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-11-27T02:34Z.

Source is very faint field line movement seen beyond the E limb in GOES SUVI 304/284 imagery, with a small amount of material (it did not fully escape and become ejecta) possibly associated with the eruption, starting around 2024-11-27T08:50Z. General field line movement and a very gradual 'thinning'/dimming/opening of field lines can be seen when toggling through GOES SUVI 284 imagery between 2024-11-27T08:00Z-14:00Z. GOES SUVI used for analysis; outage in SDO affecting all SDO data product timestamps starting at about 2024-11-26T23:52Z.

The filament extends southeastwards from Active Regions 13905 (S09E01) and 13906 (S16E08). The CME also has a second, follow-up front - a loop seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-11-27T20:36Z. Only one frame for this CME is available in STEREO A COR2 because of an extensive data gap.

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and one frame of STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption  visible on or just beyond the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-11-27T19:26Z.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Slow, wide, outflow-like CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO and to the west-northwest in STEREO A COR2. Likely associated with far-sided activity at high northern latitudes.

note: Loop CME with internal filamentary structure seen due south in SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2; the source of this CME is likely the eruption of a SE hanging filament starting around 2024-11-29T12:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304, 284 and STA EUVI 195 and centered ~S35E20.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME seen to the east-southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3; associated with a minor eruption near an equatorial active region near the eastern limb seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-11-2919:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an eruption visible near the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-30T05:30Z which exhibits a clear southern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible on/near the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 284 and 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-30T10:40Z. An opening of field lines is visible over the eastern limb at this time in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A CME to the west where the source is a loop-like filament eruption seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting after 2024-12-01T02:16Z. There are post-eruptive arcades and dimming seen in SUVI 284/195 and in STEREO A EUVI 195. The filament is centered at ~N20W40 in STEREO A so the source is at ~N20W70, as seen in GOES SUVI and SDO.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor jet (or rather the first in a series of minor southward jets). The source has not been found and is possibly backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery for a few frames following a data gap. The source is likely an eruption near the eastern limb seen in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 starting around 2024-12-01T21:30Z. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Diffuse CME with little to no leading edge seen to the east-south-east in SOHO LASCO C2 and also in STEREO A COR2. Associated with opening and moving field lines behind the southeastern limb seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 06:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-02T16:36Z. CME also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3. The CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is likely from beyond the SE limb at approximately -95 to -105 degrees longitude based on comparison with two previous CMEs (2024-12-01T22:00Z and 2024-12-02T07:12Z) that are very similar.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-02T19:36Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3. There is no clear or definitive coronal signature, so the source of this CME is likely far-sided. There are some faint moving field lines off the SW limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2024-12-02T17:00Z that continue for a few hours that could be associated with this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-03T01:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption beyond the SW limb as seen in GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 195 and 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint loop CME to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME was not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to overnight data gap which lasted from 2024-12-03T12:23Z to 2024-12-04T00:38Z. Source is a filament eruption seen on the NW limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-12-03T20:16Z. This filament is located directly on or just beyond the limb (W90-W110 or so) and spans from N10-N25. Note: The timing of this candidate source is indeed very close to the start time of the CME, which may evoke skepticism about this truly being the source, but due to the congruency between the location and shape of this source with this CME as well as a subsequent source identified which matches well with the CME seen one frame later at 12:48Z, there is a slight increase in confidence that this eruption is indeed a strong candidate source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to overnight data gap which lasted from 2024-12-03T12:23Z to 2024-12-04T00:38Z. Source is likely a small jet-like eruption of material seen on or just beyond the NW limb (W90-W110) and at about N15 in GOES SUVI 304 (seen most clearly at later frame 2024-12-03T20:56Z) immediately following an on-limb filament eruption which had likely resulted in a preceding northwest CME: 2024-12-03T20:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the SE seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an M2.3 flare with peak time 2024-12-04T10:00Z as well as rising and opening loops of field lines which begin simultaneously with the flare and from the same location, as seen in GOES SUVI 131. The location of this source is an unnumbered region directly on the East limb, located at S10E90 at the time of the flare.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible near the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery starting around 2024-12-05T00:30Z. A rising loop is visible over the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 171 and dimming is visible near the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 195 imagery around this time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with diffuse leading edge seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and north in STEREO A; likely associated with far-side activity, though could possibly be associated with a point source eruption located near N35E02, with some flickering field lines in the north seen around 02:45Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO/STEREO A COR2 associated with an M2.5-class solar flare and subsequent eruption from near Active Region 3906 occupying very close to the southwestern limb. The CME becomes appear bright in initial imagery and well-defined and becomes more diffuse with time, eventually losing its leading edge.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast CME with protruding/faster nose seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by moving field lines seen off the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only, missed in STEREO COR2A due to a data gap spanning this event. The source for this CME appears to be far-sided, and may be continued outflow following the larger, fast CME 2024-12-05T15:48Z which was analyzed far-sided to S47E124. Field line movement over the SSE limb in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-05T16:30Z may correlate to this event, but this movement may just be continued from 2024-12-05T15:48Z as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-05T20:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap from 2024-12-05T12:09Z to 2024-12-06T00:38Z. The source of this event is clear field line opening seen along or just beyond the SW limb as seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME with a fairly narrow shape but a type of "hook" at the end visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery (more easily identified in difference imagery). There isn't a clear source, however there is some moving/opening field lines along the SW of GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-06T23:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a filament eruption near N10E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 06/01:15Z with associated moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284 and dimming in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, outflow-like CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. This CME was not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which lasted from 2024-12-06T15:53Z to 2024-12-06T19:53Z. Source is subtle and slow field line movement from on or beyond the SW limb, seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting as early as 2024-12-06T13:00Z with a slightly more distinct outflow of material seen at about 14:10Z. Opening field lines on the SW limb can also be seen in GOES SUVI 195 at 14:20Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint, puff-like CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge becomes completely diffuse before reaching halfway through C2's field-of-view. The source is uncertain. One candidate source is an area of dimming seen centered at about N10W40 starting at 2024-12-06T18:00Z in GOES SUVI 284, accompanied by a small amount of brightening from AR 13910 (N16W60) and/or AR 13918 (N13W57). Another candidate source is subtle field line movement on or beyond the NW limb seen in GOES SUVI 284/195. This CME was not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which lasted from 2024-12-06T15:53Z to 2024-12-06T19:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There are a lot of overlapping fronts following the initial front of this CME. There are two potential sources, one is moving/opening field lines beyond the limb as seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 02:30Z. There is also some movement in the AR's 13912 and 13913 starting around 02Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like/outflow-like CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a very small faint eruption near N20E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-07T03:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint front overlapping with the 2024-12-07T04:12Z CME. No clear source was found for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, although there is minor activity from the Active Region 13913 and north of it going on all morning.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like/outflow-like CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a very small faint eruption near N20E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-07T06:50Z. (Follows very similar path to the CME first seen at 2024-12-07T04:24Z).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint narrow CME in the southwest following the 2024-12-07T04:12Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Initially bright but very messy front to the SW in COR2A and C2. The source is the wide opening/movement of field lines on/behind the SW limb in EUVI A 195 (so at longitudes >=120 deg) around 20:05Z. The (very messy) ejecta/filament eruption is also seen in EUVI A 304 on/behind the limb at 2024-12-07T20:15Z after a data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a small eruption from Active Region 13916 (S16E13) starting around 2024-12-08T04:10Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery which appears to deflect towards the southeast.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME with an additional narrow portion on the southern edge that protrudes in front of the leading edge of the main flux rope shape seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption and X2.2 flare from AR 3912 (S07W52) which peaked at 2024-12-08T09:06Z. Dimming and opening field lines are seen starting at 2024-12-08T09:04Z in GOES SUVI 195/171 spanning from S20W50 to N05W50, with field line movement reaching as far as N20. Ejecta can also be seen in GOS SUVI 304 which can first be seen starting at 2024-12-08T09:24Z, but was likely initiated with the flare. Flare, dimming, and ejecta can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 at 2024-12-08T09:05Z and 09:15Z, respectively.

note: CME faintly seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear, and may be one of several minor candidate source eruptions on the disk, including some brightening from AR 3917 (near S05E05) starting around 2024-12-09T01:56Z in GOES SUVI 195 or some faint dimming starting around 2024-12-09T01:00Z around S50E10 in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk which agree with the measured longitude of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a faint and minor eruption centered near S50E40 as seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery around 2024-12-09T23:10Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME associated with a thin, southward deflecting ejecta seen in the SSE in SUVI 304 around 02:52 and possibly associated with the C9.7 from AR 3922. This southward directed deflection of ejecta and CME is peculiar to today's events from Active Region 3922.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A relatively narrow CME associated withthe M6.4 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72), with a narrow southward-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-12-10T04:48Z. Because the sequence of flare/ejecta/CME events is very fast for this and the 2024-12-10T07:24Z CME the attribution to the linked flare is not absolutely certain.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is likely associated with the M1.4 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72) and is also associated with a thin southward-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in the southwest in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting at 2024-12-10T07:16Z but best seen after 07:28Z. Because the sequence of flare/ejecta/CME events is very fast for this and the 2024-12-10T07:00Z CME (which is associated to the preceding M5.6 flare from the same active region), the exact attribution to the linked flare for these two CMEs is not absolutely certain.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very slow CME/outflow that follows even slower outflows/fronts that start as early as 2024-12-10T02Z. The source of it could be continuous activity in AR 3920 since this morning (~ location N22E37 at 02Z) which is marked by brightening in SUVI 195. After 08Z there is a minor dimming around this Active Region which could mark the eruption that might be associated with the 2024-12-10T09:53Z front.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME associated with M1.5 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72) and a narrow but eventually fan-shaped wide, south-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in the southeast in SUVI 304/284 and on southeast limb in EUVI A 195 starting at 2024-12-10T11:00Z.

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery and at least one frame of STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is a data gap for the majority of this event in STEREO A COR2 imagery with the exception of a single frame at 2024-12-10T14:38Z. The source is unclear but could be a small eruption from AR 13920.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and possibly C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The source appears to be a C2.8 flare from AR 13920 (N22E27) with a visible eruption and associated filament ejecta starting around 2024-12-10T14:10Z in GOES SUVI 304 and 131 with the ejecta deflected NE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event. The source appears to be far-sided with moving/opening field lines visible along the S/SE limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-10T15:42Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The potential source for this CME is an eruption with filament ejecta from AR 13920 (N22E24) starting around 2024-12-10T16:20Z in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and possibly C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The source appears to be a filament ejecta eruption from AR 13920 (N22E28) starting around 2024-12-10T17:08Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304 with deflection to the NE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event. The source appears to be an M1.6 class flare from AR 13922 (S18E70) with a sympathetic eruption to the west of this region starting around 2024-12-10T17:58Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 304, and 284. Moving/opening field lines are visible along the limb as well as a minor EUV wave to the south along the limb as seen in GOES SUVI 284 and 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The source for this CME is possibly a small eruption from AR 13920 (N22E21) starting around 2024-12-10T20:58Z as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME to the northeast, with messy, fuzzy, dimpled front. This CME islikely associated with minor activity in AR 13920 (N15E23).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively slow and wide CME seen to the south in SOHO LASCO imagery and southeast in STEREO A COR2. Very similar in appearance to the far-sided 2024-12-11T12:12Z CME, there are a few sources on the Earth-facing disk including an eruption on the western portion of the disk, but triangulation strongly suggests this event is far-sided. No candidate sources for this CME were observed in EUV imagery. The CME is quite difficult to measure in LASCO C2 with the CME off the southeast (CME: 2024-12-11T06:24Z) obscuring the CME in question (more evidence this is far-sided).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Another CME with an asymmetric shape in the "AR 3922 style". It is associated with the M1.9 flare from AR 3922 (S17E55), however the opening of field lines we see in in SUVI 284 seems to be further south from AR 3922. There is also opening of field lines in SUVI 171 closer to this AR.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor CME with messy/fuzzy front with the possible source a lower C-class flare from Active Region 3920, with very minor dimming/possibly faint ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 193/284.

note: Narrow CME with fuzzy front to the northeast, with no clear front in SOHO LASCO C2 and likely associated with the M2.7 flare from Active Region 3920 (N22E18) and the narrow NNE ejecta seen at 2024-12-11T10:36 in SUVI 304 at the time.

Also seen to the southwest in STEREO A COR2, suggesting it is far-sided. Likely associated with very faint, fluttering field line movement seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-11T12:00Z.

note: Far-sided halo CME with brighter bulk seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and also a fainter, torus-shaped shock with wider extent in the equatorial regions. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by expulsion and rapidly flickering field lines as seen off the south limb best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-11T21:00Z.

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and north in STEREO A COR2 with faster/protruding leading edge/nose feature. Likely associated with far-sided activity as few, if any, sources were observed in GOES SUVI on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively slow and minor CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, seemingly associated with point-source eruption from AR 3916 (S14W46) with some southward deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Not seen well in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

The source is a slow-rising loop visible near or slightly beyond the southwest limb which erupts around 2024-12-12T23:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb at this time in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 imagery as well.
