Following the data gap, the CME is visible into the SOHO LASCO C2/C3 field of view, so the start time is likely a bit earlier than the time stated. This event is visible in STEREO A COR2 after a data gap ending at 2024-12-13T00:53Z for only a few frames. The source is an eruption visible from beyond the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting around 2024-12-12T23:16Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and the south/southwest in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a C2.1 flare starting at 2024-12-13T02:21Z from old Active Region 3916 (currently a plage), around S15W55. The eruption is best seen with brightening and an ejecta of material in GOES SUVI 304. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304. The CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Partially overlaps in the field of view of the coronagraphs with CME: 2024-12-13T02:48Z. The source is likely an M1.0 flare starting at 2024-12-13T03:11Z from AR 3922 (S18E37) with dimming, opening field lines best seen in GOES SUVI 195/284 as well as an ejecta of material in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is a filament eruption centered around S35E30 with liftoff starting around 2024-12-13T06:48Z as best seen in GOES SUVI 304. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME faintly visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-13T11:38Z. The source is not clearly visible in available EUV imagery, and the CME may originate from the far side.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME seen predominantly to the south in SOHO LASCO imagery during a STEREO A data gap. May be potentially associated with an M1.0 flare from AR 3922 starting at 2024-12-13T14:15Z, but there is no clear eruption of material leading to a CME associated with it. There is some faint dimming seen in GOES SUVI 284 at 14:26Z, close in time to when this was in the coronagraphs. Initial analysis suggests this eruption originates from the far-side, but triangulation with STEREO A data is probably necessary to confirm front-sidedness.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor narrow outflow seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A COR2 data gap; the source is uncertain, but could potentially be associated with dimming near center disk seen best around 2024-12-13T18:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Fast, thin CME seen to the SSE in all coronagraphs. The source appears to be a small filament eruption from AR 3922 (S16W24), best observed in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-12-14T01:28Z, which then deflects sharply southward after erupting. This eruption is notably close to the CME start time, but it is the best candidate and the filament shape in GOES SUVI aligns visually with the coronagraph signature.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the SW only in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO COR2A was available at this time but this CME isn't observed there. The source is likely near/south of Active Region 3916 decayed to a plage, with a narrow filament ejecta observed in GOES SUVI 304 around S20W70 starting around 2024-12-14T02:36Z. The CME precedes a similarly shaped, brighter and more distinct 2024-12-14T05:36Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Thin minor jet only seen in SOHO LASCO imagery but not in STEREO A COR2. No source for this CME has been found on the disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME likely associated with minor flare and filament eruption seen around ~2024-12-14T05:12 near/south of Active Region 3916 decayed to a plage (~S15W69) or alternatively a less certain eruption of very long filament along longitude ~S25 centered around 35-40 deg longitude, maybe seen erupting in SUVI 304/284 (but it is more likely that the matter fell back). The CME is preceded by a similarly shaped even fainter 2024-12-14T04:00Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint northern CME with the source an eruption starting around 2024-12-14T09:20Z in the NW quadrant centered ~(N34W60), as seen in SUVI 195/304/284, with narrow ejecta in 304 to the N and dimming/minor post eruptive arcades in 195/284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: No source has been found for this very slow CME with multiple fronts.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The source of this faint CME with a fuzzy front could be a super minor filament off or close to the SW limb seen in SUVI 304 around 2024-12-14T21:44.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrowish CME in the southwest. Its source could be the southwestern eruption/ejecta from AR 3916 (S15W81) seen in SUVI 304 at 2024-12-14T23:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast CME to the west, the beginning of which is covered by a data gap in SOHO. Its source was hard to identify since there are multiple eruption close to SW limb near this time, as well as a faint movement of field lines likely beyond the W limb in SUVI 171/195 at 2024-12-15T00:50Z. In EUVI A 195 near the west limb (in STEREO) there are post-eruptive arcades seen at ~2024-12-15T01:05Z after the long data gap. The very approximate location of this  source in STEREO A is ~110 degrees.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, 3-part CME visible to the S/SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery starting around 2024-12-15T01:25Z. The source of this CME is a long filament stretched from W10 to W60 along the S25 latitude that erupts starting around 2024-12-14T21:50Z with full lift off by 2024-12-14T23:50Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304. Associated moving/opening field lines are visible along the SW in GOES SUVI 284. Sympathetic eruption appears to occur around/within AR 13924 which is visible as brightening in GOES SUVI 195. Additionally, post-eruptive arcades are visible in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint partial halo CME first seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-12-15T04:23Z, as well as faintly in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. This CME overlaps with previous CME: 2024-12-15T01:25Z, making the front difficult to track in SOHO LASCO. The source of this event appears to be an area of dimming centered near AR 3924 (S19W18) as seen GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME overlapping a bright streamer to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a C-class flare and associated filament ejecta from decayed AR 13916 (S15W85) visible in GOES SUVI 304, 284, 131, and STEREO A EUVI 304 starting around 2024-12-15T09:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME with core visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap beginning at 15/11:38Z in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME. The CME has a faint halo shock visible in later frames. The source appears to be far sided with wide moving/opening field lines to the SE in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-15T14:19Z. A portion of the front appears to be moving faster than the rest of the CME which may be indicative of an overlapping CME. However, due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints and lack of a separately identifiable source, this feature was excluded in the measurement of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet-like CME first seen in the SSE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3. A majority of this event is obscured by a data gap in STEREO A COR2A lasting from from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. There is no clear source seen for this CME as it is likely far sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:24Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is limited COR2A imagery for this event due to a data gap from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. There is no clear source seen for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. The source of this event appears to be an area of field line movement seen along the SE limb (approx. S15E90) as seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. There is not a clear source candidate for this CME. Field line movement was visible on the west limb in GOES SUVI 195, but no clear source on the disk could be found. This CME may originate on/beyond the west limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very narrow jet CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery but not observed in STEREO A COR2. Possibly associated with a minor eruption located near the vicinity of AR 3926 (S20E55), but the source of the eruption is unclear, as the EUV signature doesn't show a definite jet signature.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Minor and relatively faint CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and not seen well in STEREO A COR2 data. Likely associated with moving field lines from an active region rotating onto the Earth-facing disk at perhaps a longitude between -80 and -90 degrees, as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor, relatively slow CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 along a minor streamer. Associated with a minor eruption near N32E80 as evidenced by opening field lines seen best in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption starting at 2024-12-17T03:52Z in GOES SUVI 304 around S10E80. Opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 171/195/284. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption that appears to have a footpoint located at approximately S40E40 and a footpoint that wraps beyond the east limb as seen in available GOES SUVI imagery. Filament liftoff is seen starting at 2024-12-17T06:40Z in GOES SUVI 304. Dimming and opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 195 and opening field lines are seen in GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195 and 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME faintly visible to the southwest in STEREO A COR2. This CME not was clearly seen in any available SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source was also not found. The CME fades away after a few frames of STEREO A COR2 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the east in SOHO LACSO C2/C3, not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-17T11:36Z. The source is not clearly visible, and it may be farsided. Field line movement may be seen near the limb in GOES SUVI 171/195/284 from approximately 2024-12-17T07:00Z to 13:00Z, but no clear eruption is seen and no source location can be determined.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast, farsided halo CME in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 in real time due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-17T11:38Z. Faint, wide field line movement is seen on the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-12-17T15:59Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T06:36Z. Also visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C3 and in white light only to the NW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely an eruption from south of AR 3920 (N12W90) starting around 2024-12-18T05:56Z in GOES SUVI 284. Another source possibility is a spot of activity a few degrees north (~N16W85) that also "erupted" around 2024-12-18T05:36Z. Both source candidates are bright in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T10:00Z. Also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3. The majority of this CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:38Z. The source of this CME is most likely some moving field lines on or just behind the E limb beginning around 2024-12-18T07:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T11:12Z. Also visible to the NW for a couple frames in SOHO LASCO C3 but is very faint. CME is mostly covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:38Z. The source of this CME is most likely some minor brightening and general, continuous activity best seen in GOES SUVI 304 from AR 3920 in the NW for a few hours prior to and after the CME first emerges into SOHO LASCO C2, but there is no clearly definitive source candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T12:48Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:38Z. A possible source of this CME is some very minor activity to the north of AR 3924 at approximately S06W70 best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2024-12-18T10:31Z. It is also possible that the source of this CME is far-sided as there is not a definitive source candidate on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint loop CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is very likely the eruption of a small filament starting around 2024-12-18T14:49Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304, which was seen on the disk spanning approx. S05W70 to S22W65, near Active Region 3924 (S20W65). Part of this CME is not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T18:24Z. Also visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no definitive source candidate on the Earth-facing disk, so this CME is likely far-sided. A far-sided source is consistent with measurements.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint "puffy" CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. This CME is not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-12-18T18:53Z to 2024-12-19T01:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the NE is SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-19T01:25Z. Also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is very faint in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is likely a large rising loop of field lines seen from beyond the NE limb in GOES SUVI 284, first noticeable starting at 2024-12-19T00:39Z. There is some minor influence seen in the NE quadrant of the Earth-facing disk, but this eruption appears much more likely to be far-sided. A far-sided source is also consistent with measurements.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, jet-like CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-19T03:48Z that is easier to see in running difference imagery. This CME does not make it beyond the field-of-view of SOHO LASCO C2 and is not visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely a small amount of activity and brightening starting about 2024-12-19T01:45Z best seen in GOES SUVI 304 on the W limb at about N10. This is just to the SW of AR 3920 which was at about N22W83 at the time of eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-12-19T14:00Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a filament eruption from on or beyond the SW limb. The prominence material can be seen lifting off the SW limb in both GOES SUVI 284 and 304 starting about 2024-12-19T12:53Z. This filament eruption is overtaken by a far-sided halo CME with start time 2024-12-19T17:53Z in STEREO A COR2. This CME is only discernible by itself in SOHO LASCO C2 and a couple of frames in SOHO LASCO C3. The majority of the CME is obscured by and blends in with the far-sided halo later in its propagation into the fields-of-view of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Halo CME first seen in STEREO A COR2 at 2024-12-19T17:53Z. The bulk of the CME is to the SW. This CME is also seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This start time was chosen based on when the CME was first seen in available imagery at the time of analysis, but the actual start time is earlier. The source of this CME is most likely far-sided. There are no good source candidates on the Earth-facing disk, and coronal signatures from beyond the SW limb suggest a far-sided source.  In GOES SUVI 284, there is some flickering in the farthest out field lines over the SW limb across most of the SW quadrant first seen at about 2024-12-19T16:19Z. There is also some very faint ejecta seen from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting about 2024-12-19T16:21Z. Measurements are consistent with a far-sided source. This CME also overlaps with a prior filament eruption to the SW.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the east in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The start of the CME is not seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 due to a data gap from 2024-12-19T21:36Z to 2024-12-20T02:00Z. There is not a clear source on the disk, but there is some activity seen as moving field lines on the east limb leading up to the CME, around latitude S10, starting at 2024-12-19T22:27Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet seen to the WSW in C2/C3/COR2A, potentially associated with a visible filament eruption seen near 2024-12-20T22:30Z seen in the southwest portion of the disk. Triangulation of this event in measurement software suggests it may be potentially associated with one of two filament eruptions occurring near simultaneously seen best in GOES SUVI 304, one near the southern polar crown and one near about S40W35, both filament eruptions having notable southern deflection. Based on the measurement, the filament near S40W35 seems to be better the source candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME with trianglular/trapezoidal shaped leading edge seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO and farther to the west in STEREO A; was initially theorized to be associated with front-sided filament eruptions on the Earth facing disk in the southwest limb around 2024-12-19T22:00Z, however, triangulation suggests that this eruption is far-sided. Possibly associated with a far-sided eruption corresponding starting around 01:00Z that erupts distinctly different than the filament eruption seen in GOES 304 seen best in GOES 93/171/284 composite imagery off the southern limb and propagating to the southwest.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a fuzzy front seen mostly in STEREO A COR2, with SOHO imagery very poor quality at the time of this event. No source has been found for this event.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. In real time, the CME is not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 after a data gap from 2024-12-20T11:18Z to 2024-12-20T15:06Z. The source is likely an eruption from AR 3932 (approx, S18E70) in the southeast, associated with a C9.4-class flare starting at 2024-12-20T10:03Z. The flare and brightening are best seen in GOES SUVI 131, and the eruption is also seen with an ejecta of material and field line movement in GOES SUVI 195/284. The eruption is also visible on the SE limb in STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME to the southwest with a possible source a very minor movement/opening of field lines behind the southwest limb around 2024-12-20T21:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint narrow CME/outflow with a fuzzy front to the south after a data gap, with no clear source found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow faint CME to the E. A minor eruption off the southeast limb seen in SUVI 195 around 2024-12-20T21:05Z with movement/opening of field lines seen in SUVI 284 starting 21:15Z was explored as a source, however the fit with two coronagraphs doesn't support the longitude close to -90 deg.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely an eruption centered around N20E10 starting around 2024-12-20T21:27Z with dimming observed in GOES SUVI 195. Post-eruptive arcades are seen in SDO AIA 284/304.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, directly following CME: 2024-12-21T21:12Z in the field of view of the coronagraphs. The potential source is near or beyond the west limb as seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUV imagery. In GOES SUVI 304, ejecta can be seen departing on the limb starting at 2024-12-20T23:00Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 195/284 and STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely on the far side, and rapidly opening field lines are visible beyond the NE limb in GOES SUVI 195/284 starting at 2024-12-21T09:20Z. Field line movement is also faintly visible in STEREO A EUV 195 imagery. The CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-21T11:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source location is near the west limb as seen from GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUV imagery. Opening field lines can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-12-21T11:19Z. This can also be faintly seen in STEREO A EUV imagery. Brightening and an ejecta of material can be seen on the west limb in GOES SUVI 304, around S20, possibly near AR 3924, which rotated off of the Earth-facing disk on 2024-12-21.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2 along a streamer prior to a data gap starting at 2024-12-21T11:39Z. The start time is likely earlier, as part of this CME was visible in the coronagraphs as early as 2024-12-21T06:00Z, but did not start picking up speed and moving through the coronagraphs until around 2024-12-21T13:25Z. The source is unclear, and it is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME and possible shock first seen in the SSW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-21T17:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is immediately followed by a slower, more southern CME.

The signature in GOES SUVI 284 is characterized by a destabilizing arcade south of the active region and broad dimming signature. Associated with a type II radio burst with observed shock speed of 1064 km/s.

This measurement generally focuses on the faster, southeastern component as observed from SOHO LASCO. Moving field lines seen off the southeastern limb in GOES SUVI 284 suggest this eruption is far-sided.

note: Faint CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A, notably more faint in COR2A and barely visible in COR2A running difference imagery. The source for this CME is uncertain, as it appears to form early in the LASCO C2 FOV rather than moving out from the occulting disk, but there are two potential candidates if it does start on-disk. A small filament eruption from AR 3933 (~S07W55) starting at 2024-12-28T07:56Z in GOES SUVI 195/304 fits the measured longitude well but not latitude, and there is also field line movement beginning on the NW limb (~N18) around 2024-12-28T08:08Z in GOES SUVI 195 that doesn't fit longitude but is a more northward latitude. Both sources time well but are off on other parameters, AR 3933 is a closer match so it has been analyzed as the most likely.

The CME front is initially quite faint in early C2, almost appearing to manifest in the FOV rather than emerging from the occulting disk, but it is much better viewed in C3 and COR2A. No source was observed in GOES SUVI imagery, but it triangulated well far-sided and bears resemblence to other SE fronts such as CME: 2024-12-27T22:00Z.

The attached WSA-Enlil+Cone simulation should not be interpreted as a forecast and is likely to overestimate geomagnetic impacts at Earth given that the measurement represents the faint shock associated with the CME, which does not contain much observed material behind the leading edge.

The tops of post-eruptive arcades can be seen emerging from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 171 starting at about 2025-01-07T23:48Z. note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and in STEREO COR2A starting at 2025-01-27T02:23Z returning from a data gap. The source for this CME is likely narrow filament ejecta from AR 3961 around 2025-01-27T23:28 in SDO AIA 304, located on the west limb around S10W90 at this time. Weak field line movement on/near the NW limb near cluster of ARs 3971/3965/3962, best observed in GOES SUVI 171 around 2025-01-27T23:25Z, creates a diffuse overlapping coronagraph signature to the NW of this more clear signature traveling SW.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is observed on/just beyond the SW limb as filament ejecta visible in SDO AIA 131/171/193/304 starting at 2025-01-27T00:15Z, and is likely AR 3961 (S10W90 at time of eruption).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-27T11:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament ejection beginning at 2025-01-27T10:32Z seen just around the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-27T16:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-01-27T15:38Z. The source of this CME is field line movement and dimming seen near AR 3972 (S19W57) in SDO AIA 171 and 193 beginning at 2025-01-27T14:54Z. The dimming expands to the South of the Active Region suggesting a Southern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-27T17:36Z. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2A due to a data gap beginning at 2025-01-27T15:38Z, and fades before entering the field-of-view in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this event is field line movement seen along the South limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 beginning at 2025-01-27T16:59Z, suggesting a far sided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and SW in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption from AR 13961 (S10, approx. W105-110) just beyond the SW limb. Brightening is seen in STEREO A EUVI 195/304 imagery at S10W110 (coordinates from perspective of Earth-facing disk) at 2025-01-28T08:05Z. Opening field lines are seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 starting at 2025-01-28T08:05Z, and the absence of post-eruptive arcades and/or dimming on the Earth-facing disk further suggests this eruption is beyond the SW limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-01-28T20:12Z. CME is also seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C3 and is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is possibly a small eruption from near the E limb (~S07).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the SW with the source the minor opening of field lines on/likely behind the SW limb starting at 2025-01-29T18:33Z as seen in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in SOHO LASCO C2 due to a data gap from 30/04:00Z to 30/07:36Z. The source of this CME is field line movement seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284, suggesting a far sided source location.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen to the SW beginning at 2025-01-30T09:12Z, as well as by STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is overtaken by CME: 2025-01-30T11:12Z in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is rising field line loops seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-30T11:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195, indicating a far sided source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. CME not captured by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which started at 2025-01-30T15:09Z. The source is a filament eruption seen beginning at approx. 2025-01-30T13:49Z in SDO AIA 304, spanning approx. S05E05 to S40E40. Dimming and post eruptive arcades are also visible in SDO AIA 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint partial-halo CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, which remains visible into the C3 field of view. Overlaps with CME:2025-01-30T16:12Z, which is much more well-defined in coronagraph imagery. This CME is not captured by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which started at 2025-01-30T15:09Z. The source of this CME is a distinct set of opening field lines and post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94/171/193 around 2025-01-30T14:25Z located at approx. S15E10, as part of the same filament eruption which sourced CME:2025-01-30T16:12Z, which was seen beginning at approx. 2025-01-30T13:49Z in SDO AIA 304, spanning approx. S05E05 to S40E40.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Loop CME seen to the West in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME is not captured by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which started at 2025-01-30T15:09Z. The source of thus event is field line opening seen along/from just beyond the Western limb starting at 2025-01-30T17:57Z in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the W/NW. The source is an M6.7 flare from AR13978 (N14E43), based on SDO/AIA 131 imagery, peaking at 2025-01-31T14:06Z. Associated filament ejecta is visible in SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2025-01-31T13:51Z. Moving/opening field lines and EUV wave are also visible along the NW limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-01-31T14:00Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow eruption seen to the west in SOHO/STEREO A associated with a minor eruption near the vicinity of Active Region 13979 near S10W55, exhibiting some westward deflection seen in GOES 284/304 and SDO 193/171/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor, faint loop appearing to the west-northwest in SOHO LASCO imagery following behind the outflow of CME: 2025-02-01T14:24Z to the west. Likely associated with a far-sided eruption as evidenced by moving field lines seen off the northwest limb best in GOES 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Asymmetric loop CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by a breaking/disappearing magnetic field line/loop seen far off the southwestern limb in GOES 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as a far-sided halo directed towards the south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, with a fast opening of field lines visible over the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2025-02-02T05:38Z. Eruptive material is also visible over/beyond the southwest limb starting around 2025-02-02T06:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 imagery. It is possible this event is associated with former Active Region 13961, which was located approximately around longitude 170-175 degrees at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the west/northwest in STEREO A COR2, but is it not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no corresponding signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event. There is an eruption visible beyond the southwest limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery starting around 2025-02-02T10:15Z and again around 13:15Z, but both of these eruptions appear too far south to be associated with this event.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely associated with an eruption and M5.1 flare from Active Region 13977 (N20E03) starting around 2025-02-02T14:00Z which deflects to the northeast as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 and GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T18:36Z. This event is too faint to be reliably tracked in SOHO LASCO C3 and is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 02/15:23Z. The source of this event is field line movement seen near AR 3977 (N19E04) beginning at approx. 2025-02-02T18:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Far sided halo CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T21:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is far sided field line opening seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This CME overlaps with CME: 2025-02-02T22:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Far sided halo CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T21:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is far sided field line opening seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This CME overlaps with CME: 2025-02-02T21:24Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T23:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 02/15:23Z. The source of this CME is an M4.1 flare from Active Region 3981 (N05E25) beginning at 02/23:04Z. This flare can be seen in SDO AIA 131 along with field line opening seen exhibiting a Southern deflection seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and in STEREO A COR2 following a data gap from 2025-02-02T15:23Z to 2025-02-03T02:53Z. The source may be related to a faint opening of field lines observed over the southeast limb starting around 2025-02-03T00:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption spanning S45W40 to S35W80 which begins to lift-off around 2025-02-03T11:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well. The eruption exhibits a southern deflection, which was confirmed in the measured parameters.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast asymmetrical and relatively narrow CME to the SE, covered by a data gap in STEREO A. It source is a narrow filament eruption seen at 2025-02-04T00:02Z in SUVI 284/304 and AIA 304 on SE limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Streamer-like loop CME seen due north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and northeast in STEREO A COR2. The source is a large rising loop seen over the N/NE limb in GOES SUVI 284 seen starting at 2025-02-03T20:38Z. Corresponding field line movement on the Earth-facing disk centered over a large cluster of Active Regions in the northern hemisphere (ARs 13976, 13977, 13978, 13981, and 13982) and minor post-eruptive brightening seen at N30E20 at 2025-02-04T08:38Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and south in STEREO A COR2. Becomes diffuse after a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3. The source is field line movement seen beyond the southern limb starting at 2025-02-04T01:48Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SSE is SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-02-04T08:24Z. Also seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C3 and to the SSW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely some very faint moving field lines visible beyond the southern limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about an hour prior to the CME start time. A far-sided source fits well with measured parameters.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3, not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is unclear but may be associated with moving/opening field lines visible along the NE limb in SDO/AIA 171 starting around 2025-02-04T09:00Z and continuing through 2025-02-04T13:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor, narrow CME seen to the south-southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, likely associated with a far-sided eruption at extreme southern latitudes as evidenced by flickering field lines in SDO AIA 171 seen off the southeast limb around 2025-02-04T21:00Z. STEREO A imagery is not available to support triangulation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-02-05T02:12Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and to the S in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a filament eruption from the SW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk easily seen across SDO EUV wavelengths. The filament is best seen beginning to lift off at approximately 2025-02-05T00:10Z in SDO AIA 304. The footpoints of the filament were located at approximately S35W27 and S30W65.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint puff-like CME seen to the east-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 coronagraph imagery and not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery except for one frame. Associated with a spray/prominence eruption taking place off the eastern limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 with strong northern/northeastern deflection. The CME is characterized by a very slow moving bulk and fainter shock-like feature which accelerates outward ahead of the bulk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor, narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2 and presumably to the south in STEREO A COR2A, seemingly associated with a far-sided minor filament eruption seen around 18:00Z to the southeast in GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 304. Triangulation suggests the CME originates from near a longitude of -145 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Relatively slow, loop CME seen to the east-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, brightly in running difference imagery and faintly in white light imagery. There are few if any sources on the Earth-facing disk or off of the east/northeast limb to suggest that this CME is associated with eruptive activity on the Earth-facing limb, therefore, it likely originates from the far-side of the solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, brightly in running difference imagery and faintly in white light imagery. Likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity as evidenced by moving magnetic field lines seen off the southeast limb best in GOES SUVI 284, but as well in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME seen to the SE fully in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S/SW potentially as a partial halo in STEREO COR2A after 2025-02-06T05:09Z, with the CME front already at the edge of its FOV when its beacon data downlink resumes. Due to this data gap timing in STEREO COR2A, the CME is observed in white light imagery but unresolvable in running difference imagery. Observed as a rapid snapping open and dimming of field lines over the SE limb centered ~S28, best observed in SDO AIA 171/193 around 2025-02-06T02:31Z and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-02-06T02:34Z. Also observed in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304 as some filament ejecta. The far-sided nature of this CME is also corroborated via fitting in swpc_cat and the lack of an on-disk signature accompanying the field line movement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright filament eruption to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is a filament eruption occurring on/beyond the NW limb as viewed from SDO AIA and GOES SUVI, first seen on the NW limb as viewed from STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-02-06T10:15Z, confirmed to be separate from the M7.6 flare (AR 13981) that occurred on the earth-facing disk at this same time. Also observed starting around 2025-02-06T10:36Z in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304, launching more explosively around 2025-02-06T11:32Z. Also seen well as the filament ejecta and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, outflow like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-06T15:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-06T15:23Z to 2025-02-07T02:53Z. The source of this event is faint field line movement seen along the South limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright lightbulb CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T03:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T08:24Z. This CME appears to fade before exiting the FOV in SOHO LASCO C2. The source of this event is an M3.2 flare from AR 3981 (N06W27) peaking at 07/07:21Z seen in SDO AIA 131. Post eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with a region of dimming seen in SDO AIA 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint CEM first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T11:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is very minor field line movement seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap; the CME is likely associated with a far-sided eruption occurring behind the southeastern limb, as evidenced best by moving field lines seen off the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. Candidate source is a small amount of brightening seen from AR 13981, followed by dimming and field line movement (centered at N00W45) just to the southwest of AR 13981, which starts at 2025-02-08T00:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. Source is an M2.0 flare and associated eruption from AR 13981 (N07W41). Opening field lines and dimming seen starting at 2025-02-08T09:09Z, best seen in SDO AIA 193. The eruption is also seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not visible in SDO AIA imagery, but an eruption can be seen just on or beyond the southwest limb in STEREO A EUV 304 imagery starting at 2025-02-08T12:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME to the northwest only seen in several SOHO LASCO C2 images and largely obscured by the pylon in C3 imagery. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A imagery. No clear coronal signatures have been found for this CME, although some very minor activity is going on in the northwest, possibly from AR 13978 (N14W77).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME to the east, with pointed and fuzzy nose. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A coronagraph imagery. Its source is a filament eruption off the east limb (N10E90) which starts around  2025-02-10T00:01Z, as seen in SDO AIA 171/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 imagery. The filament could be further behind the limb, so its longitude could differ from -90 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A super faint jet to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in STEREO A COR2 (and in difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2) and only seen in 2-3 early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C3 because of extreme faintness of this event. No source was found on the Earth-facing disk, so it is likely a farsided event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to a faint eruption visible slightly beyond the southeast limb in SDO AIA 304 imagery starting around 2025-02-10T11:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-02-10T18:09Z. The source is likely related to an eruption on/near the eastern limb starting around 2025-02-10T17:50Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A faint opening of field lines is visible over the northeast limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, becoming diffuse before leaving the C2 field of view. This CME is not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2. Source is an M1.6 flare and associated eruption from AR 13981 (N05W87). Opening field lines and brightening are seen starting around 2025-02-11T05:27Z, best seen in SDO AIA 131, but also seen in SDO AIA 171/193/304. The eruption is also seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Bright CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption and associated C5.8 flare located at N15E75. Opening field lines, a rising loop, and ejecta are seen starting at 2025-02-11T06:12Z in SDO AIA 193/171/304/131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is best observed in SDO AIA 304 as a filament eruption on the eastern limb around S10E90, beginning around 2025-02-11T17:48Z and erupting more explosively around 2025-02-11T18:04Z. Also observed as field line opening in SDO AIA 171/193, and a C7.2 flare peaking at 2025-02-11T18:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It is not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 due to the control arm. The front of this CME fades fairly quickly in SOHO LASCO C2 frames before becoming too diffuse to track. There is no clear source for this CME.

As early as 2025-02-20T18:00Z in SDO AIA 193, a loop over the NW limb can be seen beginning to slowly rise, located above or near some destabilizing filament material hovering above on the NW limb in SDO AIA 304.

note: The second in a series of three overlapping CMEs. This CME is visible to the W/slightly NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and similarly to the W/slightly NW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is part of a complex eruption taking place on the NW limb in SDO imagery. At 2025-02-21T09:24Z, a wide loop snaps open in SDO AIA 171/193, and some filamentary material rapidly rises high in the corona but fails to escape solar gravitational forces, remaining suspended in the corona for a few hours. The wide loop that snapped open is a candidate source for this CME.

A large post-eruptive arcade on the NW limb also begins around 2025-02-21T11:27Z, expanding from N10->N35 on/just inside the NW limb. This filament eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, showing post-eruptive arcades and brightening stretching from N35W60 to N15W90, near AR 3989 (~N20W85) [30 degrees have been added to all STEREO A EUVI longitudes to translate to Earth-facing disk coordinates].

The source is better seen in STEREO A EUVI with the filament on/just inside the west limb as viewed from STEREO A. At 2025-02-24T05:15Z, STEREO A was located 30.297 degrees from Earth, putting its west limb around W120.3. Here in STEREO A EUVI 304, the filament can be seen slowly rising starting at 2025-02-24T03:15Z->T5:15Z, and ejecting by the next timestamp at T05:45Z. A post-eruptive arcade follows in STEREO A EUVI 195/304. The source could be, or be near, old AR 3989, which rotated off the west limb on 2025-02-21 and would be located approximately W115-W125.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the WNW is SOHO LASCO C2. CME is also seen as a partial halo mostly to the NW in STEREO A COR2 but is obscured by the pylon is SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is very difficult to distinguish from the previous CME in white light imagery. The source is most likely associated with an M3.3 flare from AR 14000 (N17W21) that peaked at 2025-02-24T07:02Z. The flare and a region of dimming projected south of the flare are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are best seen in SDO AIA 193. There also appears to be some western deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NNW in only SOHO LASCO C2, it fades quickly in the FOV after its initial visibility from the occulting disk. No source is observed for this front in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3, but not in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-02-24T20:23Z. The source of this CME is likely associated with an eruption visible beyond the SW limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:27Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131 with associated brightening, moving/opening field lines, and an EUV wave best seen in SDO/AIA 211. Following the eruption, there were very notably post-eruptive arcades which were associated with a long duration, occulted M3.9 flare from former AR 13990 (S13W120) that peaked at 2024-02-24T23:02Z. The very beginning of the flare can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 on the W limb in the last frame (2025-02-24T20:35Z) prior to the end of a downlink period. Additionally, very fast opening field lines are visible from beyond the W limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:24Z in SDO/AIA 193, SDO/AIA 171, GOES SUVI 195, and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-02-25T12:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The beginning frames of this event in SOHO LASCO are obscured by a data gap from 25/11:12Z to 25/13:39Z. The source of this CME is an M3.6 flare from AR 3998 (S15W55) as seen in SDO AIA 131. Opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 94, 171 and 193, along with an area of dimming seen in SDO AIA 94, 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only, missed in STEREO COR2A due to a data gap. The CME travels into the pylon in C3 hindering visibility in white light and running difference imagery. The source is observed as a field line loop breaking over the NW limb around 2025-02-25T14:18Z in SDO AIA 171/193, potentially from old AR 4001 which rotated over the NW limb on 2025-02-24.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-26T06:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a filament eruption centered at approx. S10W25 exhibiting a strong Westward deflection. This filament is visible in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with dimming and post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195. A large North-South configured coronal hole is visible approximately 10 degrees to the East of the eruptive source. This coronal hole may cause deflection or acceleration of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-26T09:36Z. This event fades before exiting the FOV in C2, and is therefore not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Bright CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is a filament eruption seen near S30W70 in SDO/AIA, STEREO A EUVI and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-26T14:00Z. There is strong southern deflection of the eruption, likely due to the large coronal holes to the north and east of the source location. Field line opening is also visible in SDO/AIA 171, 193, and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in a few frames of STEREO A COR2 imagery before a data gap beginning around 2025-02-26T19:00Z. The exact start time of this CME is unclear due to the overlap with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-02-26T15:00Z. The possible source of this CME is a filament eruption beginning around 2025-02-26T11:15Z in STEREO A EUVI, GOES SUVI, and SDO/AIA 304 imagery near ~S15W90+. A slow rising loop is visible in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery along the W/SW limb starting around 2025-02-26T12:00Z which may have been fully released from the lower/middle corona when the filament eruption associated with the overlapping CME to the SW occurred.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in limited imagery in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The CME exhibits an initial faint, diffuse front with a brighter portion (more clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery) that appears to be the bulk of the CME. The source appears to be a possible filament eruption stretching along the eastern side of the large N-S oriented coronal hole located near central meridian. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-26T14:16Z. Associated dimming and post-eruptive arcades are visible in SDO/AIA 195 and GOES SUVI 284. Deflection is likely for this CME due to the large coronal holes to the west of the source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. This event is not observable in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely related to a C3.5 flare and eruption from Active Region 13996 (S16W86) starting around 2025-02-26T22:50Z as seen in SDO AIA 131 imagery. Faint field line movement is visible over the southwest limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. It is also visible in SOHO LASCO C2 following a data gap ending at 2025-02-27T07:48Z. The source is likely related to an eruption from Active Region 13996 (S16W89) starting around 2025-02-27T05:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131 and 304 imagery. Faint field line movement is visible over the southwest limb around this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint and wide loop CME first seen to the NW in STEREO A COR2 and seen after a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge is nearly fully obstructed by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. Source is likely opening loops and field line movement seen just beyond the (STEREO A) northwest limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, starting around 2025-02-27T06:25Z and located at about N20W120 (Earth-facing disk coordinates).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely Active Region 13996 (S16W90), with an eruption seen starting around 2025-02-27T11:05Z in STEREO A EUVI 195 and SDO AIA 193 imagery. Brightening and dimming are seen from the region, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193/284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-02-27T15:23Z. The source is a filament eruption, with liftoff starting around 2025-02-27T17:36Z, centered around approximately N20E80 as seen in SDO AIA 304. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171/193 and dimming is visible in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen the the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-28T08:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening seen just beyond the SW limb in SDO AIA 193. This may be related to activity from AR 3996 (S16W100) which rotated off of the Earth facing disk on 2025-02-27.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-02-28T15:23Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in SOHO LASCO C2 due to a data gap from 28/14:48Z to 28/16:24Z. The source of this event is a jet-like eruption from Active Region 4006 (N18W02), exhibiting a very strong Northeastern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright, partial halo to halo CME visible in the W/NW of SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a far-sided filament eruption visible along the NW limb of STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T16:45Z. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T17:35Z. Moving/opening field lines and an EUV wave is visible in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-02-28T17:00Z. The source is suspected to be from AR 13993 (~N15W125) based on available STEREO A EUVI data. Note that there was a simultaneous, much less significant, eruption centered at (~W01W60) at the time of the far-sided eruption associated with this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-28T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a C5.2 flare and jet-like eruption from Active Region 4006 (N18W02), exhibiting a very strong Northeastern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. This CME partially overlaps and is obscured by CME: 2025-02-28T17:12Z in later frames.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 with fainter loops following shortly behind. Associated with a point source eruption from near AR 4006 (N18W10) starting at 2025-03-01T09:18Z with very strong deflection north out of the ecliptic as evidenced by dark filamentary material jetting north in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery with a very bright core mostly on the right side of the CME. The source is a large L-shaped filament eruption stretching from ~S35W10 to ~S15E40 centered around ~S35E20 starting around 2025-03-01T17:00Z. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA, GOES SUVI, and STEREO A EUVI 304. Dimming, moving/opening field lines, and post-eruptive arcades are best visible in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO/AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery to the S/SE in the outflow of the previous CME starting at 2025-03-01T18:24Z. It is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap beginning at 2025-03-01T21:38Z. The source of this CME is a partially occulted C9.5 flare from a region just beyond the SE limb near S26E90+ as seen in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 131 imagery. A well defined loop with filament ejecta in the middle is seen lifting from the source region with clear moving/opening field lines and EUV wave to the south starting around 2025-03-01T23:00Z. There appears to be strong deflection to the south with this event as evident by the moving/opening field lines in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow faint jet to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery. Its source is likely a C2.4 class flare (and a super minor ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304) from AR 4011 (S18E58) starting at 2025-03-02T03:37Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faintest of the 3 consecutive narrow jets from AR 4011 this morning. Its source is likely the C1.2 flare from AR 4011 (S18E57) starting at 2025-03-02T05:46Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint narrow CME to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery.  Its source is likely the C2.7 flare and a minor eruption in AR 4011 (S18E54) seen in SDO AIA 131, 304 and GOES SUVI 304, 284 and on SE limb in EUVI A 195 at 2025-03-02T09:57Z. Note that there also seems to be an even more minor eruption off the SW limb at the same time seen in SDO AIA 304/ GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright heart-shaped CME to the northwest in both coronagraphs. No source has been found on the Earth-facing disk, but there is a faint flicker/movement of field lines far behind the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 seen most clearly at 2025-03-02T11:09Z but really faintly seen as early as 2025-03-02T10:15Z, and also possibly seen as a faint/indistinct movement beyond the northwest limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 at 2025-03-02T10:35Z. Most likely this is a backsided CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop only seen in COR2A running difference imagery and overlapping with the earlier more significant 2025-03-02T10:24Z CME; this event is not clearly seen in SOHO; the actual start might be earlier. No source has been found.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery, and is not seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery due to a data gap from ~2025-03-03T11:24Z to 2025-03-03T17:12Z. The source may be related to a large southwest filament eruption spanning S55W15 to S40W60 seen in SDO AIA 304 imagery starting around 2025-03-03T11:28Z. An associated dimming region is visible in SDO AIA 193 around this time centered near ~S60W20. Due to the data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery at this time, it is difficult to confirm with a triangulated measurement if this event is related to the filament eruption.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the SSE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-03T17:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a date gap 03/14:23Z to 03/21:38Z. The source of this event may be related to faint field line movement visible over the S/SE limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2025-03-03T17:00Z
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The potential source of this CME is a filament eruption centered near S27E45 (below active regions 14012 and 14011) starting around 2025-03-04T03:20Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304. Associated moving/opening field lines and possible EUV wave visible to the south and south west towards the south pole as seen in SDO/AIA 193 indicating southern deflection, likely due to the coronal hole located N/NE of the source location. Associated brightening and dimming are also visible in SDO/AIA 131, 304, and 193 in the area of the source with additional dimming visible further south closer to the south pole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME partially overlaps the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-04T03:48Z. The potential source for this CME is a filament eruption near S42W95 with associated moving/opening field lines visible along the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304 and 171 starting around 2025-03-04T03:51Z. There appears to be southward deflection possibly due to coronal holes in the vicinity of the source location. The coronal holes and the eruptions deflection are more clearly seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with diffuse front visible along streamer to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The potential source is a filament eruption centered around S25E42 (below ARs 14012 and 14011) visible in SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2025-03-04T09:30Z. Brightening and dimming are also visible in SDO/AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible on/near the southwest limb starting around 2025-03-04T18:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-04T19:38Z. The source is likely related to an eruption visible near the northwest limb (centered near ~N15W80) starting around 2025-03-04T21:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A faint CME with a fuzzy front to the northeast, closely followed by a second, brighter, front, better seen in SOHO than in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. There is a super faint wider front that might indicate a shock front. No source has been found for this CME, so it is likely far-sided.

note: Very faint flux rope CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, then seen as an extremely faint feature to the SE in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a set of loops/flux rope seen lifting off from on or just beyond the southeast limb (loop spans approx. S20-S25 and E110-E90) starting at about 2025-03-05T03:34Z in SDO AIA 171 imagery. Post-eruptive arcades appear several hours later and seemingly from the same location starting at about 2025-03-05T06:36Z in SDO AIA 171.

The source is a small filament which spanned roughly N28W55->N28W70 (centered N28W62) near AR 14006 (N18W70) at 2025-03-05T10:09Z just before erupting. The eruption is best seen in SDO AIA 304 as the filament material brightening and lifting off, and also observed in SDO AIA 171 as field line movement to the NW.

Source is a faint and narrow loop / opening field line movement can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 off the NE limb, first distinguishable at 2025-03-06T03:00Z when the loop is already near the edge of the SUVI 284 field of view. There are two candidates for the origin of this loop: 1) a very small instance of brightening at 2025-03-06T02:58Z from AR 4017 (S05E56), or 2) from just beyond the NE limb, likely located near the northernmost footpoint of the arc of field lines visible on the NE limb in UV imagery which turns into the streamer visible to the NE in coronagraph imagery.

Source is an area of dimming and opening field lines seen from AR 4016 (S26E33) and the surrounding area, which spans from S10 to S30 and E30 to E40, starting at 2025-03-06T04:39Z in SDO AIA 193. The opening field lines appear to be deflected southward and westward in SDO AIA 193/171.

Dimming is also visible in SDO AIA 193 exhibiting a strong Southern deflection. A larger coronal hole is visible to the North of this eruption sight in SDO AIA 211, which may be contributing to the Southern deflection.

The source of this event is a minor eruption seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA 304 beginning at approx. 07/02:45Z, along with faint field line opening seen in SDO AIA 193.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2. The source of this event is an area of field line opening seen along or just beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131 following the opening. This CME is almost entirely obstructed by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-03-07T14:53Z to 2025-03-07T21:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and in later STEREO A COR2 frames. Source is a filament close to the SW limb (spans S35W60 to S30W90) seen lifting off starting at 2025-03-07T18:45Z in SDO AIA 171, 193, and 304. Bright ejecta can be seen off the SW limb in SDO AIA 171 and 304, and in GOES SUVI 304 a large loop of ejected filamentary material can be seen by 2025-03-07T19:20Z, which fully departs the GOES SUVI field of view by about 2025-03-07T20:36Z.

note: Loop CME seen to the SW in both SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an M1.6 flare and eruption from AR 4016 (S26E10). Dimming with southward deflection is seen starting at 2025-03-07T20:59Z in SDO AIA 193 and spans about 10 degrees radially around AR 4016 i.e. from S15 to S35 and from E20 to E00. Opening field lines with some southward deflection can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 as well. Post-eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, including some from nearby AR 4012 (S13W06) starting at 2025-03-07T21:04Z. An EUV wave is seen propagating southward from AR 4016 in SDO AIA 193.

note: This narrow on-disk CME is seen as a faint flux rope due south in SOHO LASCO C2 and simultaneously as a faint loop to the southeast in STEREO A COR2, which is currently 30 degrees to the west of SOHO LASCO. The source is a subtle eruption from AR 4012 (S20W00) starting at 2025-03-07T21:35Z, seen as dimming, brightening, and field line opening in SDO AIA 193 and 171, as well as GOES SUVI 284 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Relatively slow, diffuse CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2. Source is an eruption seen close to the SW limb as evidenced by moving field lines seen lifting off starting as early as 2025-03-08T06:08Z best in GOES SUVI 284. The signature is also seen well by opening magnetic field lines in SDO AIA 171 and 193.

note: Narrow and fast CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery associated with a point source eruption from Active Region 14011 (S14W29) seen erupting around 2025-03-08T14:45Z in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 284. The active region footpoint is seen to have a small brightening during the eruption followed by a dark jet of plasma material leaving to the southwest with some deflection to the west.

note: Faint, narrow, somewhat asymmetrical CME to the northeast, with a protruding pointy nose. Source: minor eruption/prominence on/behind the northeast limb seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-08T22:10Z and as very minor movement of field lines behind the NE limb in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-09T11:53Z. The source is likely related to an eruption, which exhibits northern deflection, visible on or slightly beyond the northeast limb (~N30E90) starting around 2025-03-03T12:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption from Active Region 14012 (S15W40) starting around 2025-03-10T03:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. The source eruption exhibits a southeast deflection, suggesting that the CME parameters may measure southeast of the on-disk source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption visible on or slightly beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-03-10T05:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a minor eruption near Active Region 14016 (~S25W25) starting around 2025-03-10T08:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is observed in SDO AIA 193 at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint but visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is too faint to observe in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field-line movement visible over the southwest limb starting around 2025-03-10T10:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faint but visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery before the leading edge becomes too diffuse to observe. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and relatively narrow CME to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The leading edge appears slightly brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. The source is opening field lines seen starting at 2025-03-11T03:35Z located on or just beyond the W limb as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 (W120-130 from SDO AIA perspective) and spanning approximately N00 to S10 in latitude, although the eruption likely extends to farther beyond the limb. Field line movement and the disappearance of a small loop of material can be seen from the same location in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery between the 2025-03-11T03:45Z and 2025-03-11T04:45Z frames.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Super narrow jet (with the 2 degree half-width or so), seen only in SOHO LASCO C2 and faintly in a few early timestamps of C3. Not discernible in STEREO A COR2, likely because of its faintness. Likely associated with the M1.1 flare from AR 14024 (N5W47).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more directed towards the north in STEREO Ahead COR2 imagery composed of a fainter, faster shock. No sources on the Earth-facing disk in EUV imagery seem to be associated with this event, so the CME is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 during a COR2A data gap. Appears to be associated with a minor eruption from Active Region 14024 (N07W57) and C9.6-class flare as evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 294 starting around 2025-03-11T21:28Z as well as brightening visible in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap; it appears similar in appearance to the CME: 2025-03-11T18:24Z which was determined to likely be far-sided. Few, if any sources on the Earth-facing disk suggest that this CME occurs with eruptive activity on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bulbous jet-like CME to northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO, similar to the 2025-03-11T23:24Z CME. No clear source was found on disk but there are some movements of field lines behind the limb in the NE after 05Z in AIA 193. The CME is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A super faint jet to the northwest, seen mostly in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a few early timestamps of C3 and too faint to be seen in STEREO A COR2. There is no flare that can be associated with it but there is some brightening in AR 14024 after 2025-03-12T06Z seen in SDO AIA 193 and it is possibly associated with activity in this Active Region.
