note: Super faint and narrow jet only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery and in a few early C3 images and not seen in STEREO A COR2. No source has been found for this jet.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 white light imagery starting at 2025-03-12T20:04Z. Also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2. This jet may have been visible in running difference imagery shortly before it was visible in white light imagery and has a half-width of less than ten degrees. There is not a good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk; however, there are some possible post eruptive arcades on or just beyond the NE limb (approximately N35-N40) best seen in SDO AIA 171 beginning around 2025-03-12T21:15Z that could be related to this jet.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source may be field line movement in SDO AIA 171 observed over the SSW limb beginning around 2025-03-12T23:18Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO COR2A for a few frames before it fades, never reaching LASCO C3 imagery. First seen more clearly in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery at 2025-03-13T03:48Z. The source for this CME is likely field line movement in SDO AIA 171 on or just inside the SE limb starting around 2025-03-13T02:53Z, from the northern side of AR 14028.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in STEREO COR2A only, as SOHO LASCO C2/C3 is in a data gap from 2025-03-13T07:30Z -> 2025-03-13T22:10Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO AIA or STEREO A EUVI imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 composed of a bright narrow bulk and a fainter shock extending to the north and west relative to the bulk. The source is a minor eruption from near Active Region 4020 (N20E13) with northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 193, 171, 304 as early as 2025-03-13T16:49Z; darkening in SDO AIA 193, brightening in SDO AIA 304 and the appearance of a breaking loop in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and east-northeast in STEREO A COR2A composed of a bright narrow bulk extending to the northeast and second more minor outflow seen more to the north. The source may be associated with a minor eruption seen near the eastern limb around E80 as early as 2025-03-14T02:00Z; mostly in GOES SUVI 284 imagery, or the eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-14T15:25Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 14/15:53Z. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 4022 (N08E11) beginning at approx. 14/14:28Z. Dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 suggest a strong Eastern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely narrow faint jet seen mostly in running difference imagery in SOHO and STEREO A to the northeast. No clear source has been found in the EUV imagery at the time but there is a super minor ejecta in SDO AIA 304 at 01:40Z on the NE limb which may be related.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is additional wide and subtle field line movement seen on and very likely extending beyond the SW limb, best seen in STEREO A EUVI 193, and likely a direct consequence of or sympathetic eruption to a filament eruption seen starting at to lift off the southwest limb at 2025-03-15T04:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:36Z, whose source is the filament eruption on the southwest limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note:
One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption on the southwest limb, spanning from about S25W85 to S10W120 with southward deflection seen as it erupts in SDO AIA and STEREO-A EUV imagery. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:24Z, whose source is nearly simultaneous and in close proximity. 

Filamentary material is seen starting to lift off at 2025-03-15T04:09Z in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. Post-eruptive arcades can be seen in SDO AIA 193 and 171 starting at 2025-03-15T06:28Z and lasting for multiple hours. Bright material can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 as well. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 193 imagery, which has frames available after a data gap ending at 2025-03-15T03:45Z and reveals liftoff of material starting with the next frame with timestamp 2025-03-15T04:15Z. With STEREO A currently at a HEEQ longitude of 31, this vantage point reveals that there was a filament eruption and a separate but sympathetic rising loop directly next to the filament, which altogether extended from approximately S25W80 to S10W121 (coordinates listed as would be seen by SDO. STEREO A is currently at a HEEQ longitude of +31 degrees).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow faint jet seen to the northeast in a couple of early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C2. Not seen in STEREO A COR2. A possible source is a narrow bright ejecta on/behind the east limb in AIA 304 around 2025-03-15T18:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Complex-shaped, somewhat pointy-nosed and possibly partial halo CME to the southwest, seen the brightest in STEREO A COR2. Its source is behind the SW limb (both in SDO and in STEREO A) and likely associated with Active Region 4012 (now at approximately W125) which was fairly complex when it was on the Earth-facing disk; its coronal signatures are fast-opening field lines behind the SW limb in both EUV imagers starting at 2025-03-16T00:32Z, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171, EUVI A 195 and SUVI 285. Much later (after 05Z) some high post-eruptive arcades are seen in EUVI A 304 appearing from behind the limb, indicating the source that is far behind the limb, as seen from STEREO A. The much fainter shock can be best seen mostly as it pushes the streamer in the south south west towards the east. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet/outflow seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and in 2 timestamps surrounding a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint and narrow CME best seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a couple of early timestamps of C3 and fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely faint fuzzy CME/outflow/possible partial halo to the north-northwest, seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and even more faintly for a few early timestamps in C3, but not seen in STEREO A COR2, likely because of faintness. Better seen in running difference imagery. Its source is most likely the medium-size but pretty faint dimming seen starting ~2025-03-16T10:09Z, signifying eruption to the northwest of Active Region 4023 and centered (~N20W10), seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME with bulk seen to the north-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more towards the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery with faint, very wide shock developing in later frames with invisible leading edge containing lobes to the north and east in both SOHO and STEREO A imagery. The presumed source is an eruption from near the vicinity of Active Region 4032 (N35E35) seen as a dimming in SDO AIA 193 as early as 2025-03-16T18:04Z, disappearing loop structure in SDO AIA 171, and brightening in SDO AIA 304. There are two eruptions seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery emanating from the same area, one seen at 18:49Z and another which appears more Earth-directed at 20:49Z. Triangulation using SOHO and STEREO A imagery seems to more strongly support Earth-directedness and deflection westward than the EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very slow CME that looks like a slow streamer blowout, with a succession of almost identical faint fronts seen in both coronagraphs. The CME seems to accelerate, as seen in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. There is no clear source seen on the disk, although there is a super minor dimming in AIA 193 centered around N30E10 starting after 00:30Z and continuing until 05Z, but it is extremely faint.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2. Also seen to the S in STEREO A COR2 but is not seen in SOHO LASCO C3. A possible source candidate is a very small eruption far to the SE (~S60E10) best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2025-03-17T08:07Z; measurements align well with this possible source candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-03-17T11:36Z. Also seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C3 but not visible in STEREO A COR2A imagery (where it would be near center disk from the perspective of STEREO A). The source of this CME is likely a small filament eruption centered around N12W30 which starts around 2025-03-17T10:36Z and is best seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen mostly in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 but with front not well seen in C3. The source of this CME is unclear. While there are some opening field lines visible on/beyond the east limb starting around 2025-03-17T10:54Z best seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193, the fit with two coronagraphs indicates a lower longitude for the source.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow pointy-nosed CME/outflow to the north, following preceding CMEs. No clear source has been found for it on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T19:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in a second overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T20:12Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, narrow CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T20:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in an earlier overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T19:48Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T03:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.0 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.1 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-18T08:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen at approx. S30E65 in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-18T15:39Z. The source is likely related to an opening of field lines visible beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-03-18T15:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faintly visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 data due to a data gap from 2025-03-18T15:39Z to 2025-03-19T03:09Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption beyond the E/NE limb starting around 2025-03-19T00:30Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131, 171, 193, and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright streamer blowout CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is visibly wider in STEREO A COR2 imagery than in SOHO imagery. The source of this CME appears to be a complex series of eruptions beginning with an eruption near N05E05 starting around 2025-03-19T00:39Z. This eruption may have triggered additional instability of nearby magnetic field line foot points, which may be associated with the streamer itself. Dimming is clearly seen to the east of the initial eruption location starting around 2025-03-19T06:00Z. It is also around this time that the CME appears to begin to speed up in the SOHO field of view with a more clear/defined front appearing around this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and wide loop CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source is a filament eruption on or just beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, likely placing it at a longitude between W120 to W130, and spanning from approximately N10 to N40, with liftoff of filamentary material seen starting at 2025-03-19T03:45Z. Simultaneous opening field line movement can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, centered at N50, just to the north of the filament eruption, and possibly located further beyond the limb than the filament due to the faintness of this signature. A second, smaller loop of material centered at about N40 can be seen lifting off at 2025-03-19T06:15Z in STEREO A EUVI 304 which may be the source of the additional outflow seen in coronagraph imagery following this CME. Field line movement can also be seen on or beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 195. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint but fast CME with an asymmetrical front, with a protruding nose to the south, seen directed to the west in SOHO with the start covered by the nighttime data gap in SOHO. Its source is the filament eruption seen on/behind the SW limb: as ejecta/prominence in AIA 304 (there are actually two ejectas - a more southern complex shaped loop-like prominence seen at 2025-03-19T22:50Z at latitude of -21, and a fan-shaped ejecta to the north of it seen at latitude of -7 at 2025-03-19T223:46Z. This eruption is also seen as fast opening of field lines behind the limb in AIA 193/171 starting at 2025-03-19T222:01Z and later (starting at 2025-03-19T223:21Z) as bright post-eruptive arcades on/behind the limb in AIA 131. There is an associated long duration occulted C6.0 flare peaking at 2025-03-20T00:07Z from behind the limb (bright arcades). It is possible that the flare is from former Active Region 4018 (S21W100).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint loop CME visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, with a faint flux rope feature more visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is the ejection of material from just beyond the southwest limb, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and ejecta starting around 2025-03-19T23:15Z in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery. Post-eruptive brightening extends onto the disk spanning from about S10 to S15 and W80 to W90, as seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-19T23:40Z. Associated surrounding field line movement extends into the northern hemisphere on or beyond the western limb, and some northern deflection occurs as the material erupts.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME with brighter, narrower bulk and fainter shock visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. The source of the CME appears to the ejection of material from near the vicinity of Active Region 4022 just near N08W75, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and brightening starting around 2025-03-20T17:24Z in SDO AIA 193 and 304 imagery. Faint flickering field lines far off the western limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 suggest that a component of this large scale eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. This CME is slow to evolve and appear as a defined front in the LASCO C2 field-of-view, and appears more clear in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source for this CME is not observed as a distinct source, but appears to be continued outflow from CME 2025-03-20T17:12Z from AR 14022 centered at N08W75, corroborated via triangulation in the STEREO_CAT tool.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S in two available frames of STEREO COR2A before a data gap begins at 2025-03-21T15:09Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO and GOES imagery, suggesting a far-sided source alongside comparison between the CME direction in white light SOHO LASCO and STEREO COR2A imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint halo CME with a bulk visible mainly to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery (more easily seen in difference imagery). There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME appears to be a large dimming region centered near N02E07 starting around 2025-03-21T15:49Z with a southeast directionality based on the minor EUV wave visible in SDO/AIA 211 and 193 imagery. There's a large coronal hole situated E/SE of the dimming region and a separate coronal hole due west of the dimming region which may have contributed to the deflection visible on the solar disk in SDO/AIA imagery. This source location appears to be a sympathetic eruption to the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) seen to the SW in SDO/AIA 131 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. No STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME may be the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) as seen in SDO/AIA 131 and 193. There is clear dimming and moving/opening field lines visible to the SW of the eruption suggesting deflection. This may be due to a coronal hole due north of the source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the north-north-east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 (along the northern streamer). Its source is the filament eruption seen beyond the north-north-east limb starting ~2025-03-22T07:18Z in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 304/284, with coronal signatures including a large prominence/ejecta (or even double ejecta) in AIA 171, SIVI 304/284 and as faint opening of field lines in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption near Active Region 14037 (N22W32) starting around 2025-03-22T13:20Z seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N28E45 starting around 2025-03-22T13:45Z which exhibits northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N18E52 starting around 2025-03-22T13:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is visible north of the eruption site in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2025-03-22T14:00Z and an opening of field lines can be observed over the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery at this time. Additionally, post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 2025-03-22T14:30Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faint but visible as a partial halo directed towards the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is observed as a faint far-sided halo in STEREO A COR2 imagery. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, constant outflow of minor fronts to the northeast from approximately 2025-03-23T08:36Z to 2025-03-23T13:25Z, with two of the fronts being more prominent: this one is the earlier of the two, and becomes more discernible in SOHO C3 white light and running difference imagery with time. The two more prominent fronts seem to combine/overlap about halfway into C3's field-of-view around 13Z. No clear source has been found for these outflows.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Part of the constant outflow of multiple faint flows to the northeast. This front seems to be more eastward-directed compared to previous, more northern 2025-03-23T08:36Z CME/outflow. These two CMEs eventually seem to combine/overlap about halfway into C3's FOV around 13Z. No clear source has been found for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and SSE in STEREO COR2A. The source from this CME is uncertain and appears far-sided, via observed field line movement in SDO AIA 171 over the SE limb beginning around 2025-03-23T10:03Z and a triangulated STEREOCAT tool measurement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This narrow CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to an ongoing campaign. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME (less than ten degree half-width) first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 started at 2025-03-24T19:24Z. CME is also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning 2025-03-24T16:09Z. The source of this CME is possibly a small amount of ejecta from beyond the SE limb best seen in SDO AIA 304 starting at 2025-03-24T19:06Z. Some very faint field line movement from beyond the SE limb can also be seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193 starting around 2025-03-24T19:04Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The source of this event is a C4.4 class flare from AR 14028 (S16W86) which peaked at 2025-03-25T09:49Z. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with field line opening visible in SDO AIA 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a C9.5 flare from AR 14028 (S16W86) seen peaking at 2025-03-25T12:29Z. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with wide field line opening and slight dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, reduced image quality of SOHO LASCO C3 frames for timestamps following 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by the regular overnight data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.

N20E70) beginning at approx. 26/13:28Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171 and 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

E100 to E110 in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-03-26T15:01Z, as well as faint opening loops seen off the SE limb in GOES 284 at 2025-03-26T15:15Z.

There are no significant coronal signatures except for the flare itself seen in SDO AIA 131.

note: Two faint, fuzzy blobs next to each other seen to the southwest, with no clear front. The CME is seen in SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2. No clear source found, so it is likely backsided (confirmed by fit in swpc_cat).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Dimming is best seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195/304 imagery. The main bulk of the CME is preceded by a fainter, narrower loop in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-27T21:36Z that may be associated with an eruption from the same region, around S20E30.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

A subsequent wide opening of field lines can be observed in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at this time as well.

Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A very faint loop-like CME to the southeast. There is a series of consecutive faint fronts, one of which is a bit brighter than the others and has been analyzed as the main front, but this brighter front is preceded by more faint fronts. The source of this CME is possibly the M1.5 flare from AR 14048 (S15E80) peaking at 2025-03-30T01:48Z. This CME is preceded by a narrow jet seen at 2025-03-29T23:12Z. It is possible that the jet is associated with the M1.9 flare, while this CME is associated with the M1.5 flare, both from AR 14048. The exact association with flares is not certain. Coronal signatures associated with the flares are relatively minor but very clear: an opening of field lines on/close to the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-03-29T23:13Z, followed by post-eruptive arcades seen on the limb in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. There is also minor ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-03-29T23:07Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-30T02:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. The source of this event is a slow prominence eruption seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2; it is partially obscured by the pylon in C3, but its western edge is seen in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of it is likely an eruption with a very minor ejecta seen in SDO AIA 304/131/193 and GOES SUVI 284 at 2025-03-30T04:07Z just southwest of AR 4048 (S20E70) as post-eruptive arcades and small area dimming. The associated flare is a C3.5 flare observed in GOES-S, not in GOES-P, due to an eclipse.

The eruption is well seen in STEREO A EUV imagery happening to the east of AR 4035 (N16W94) and centered around ~N22W90.

The source is likely related to an eruption and M1.5 flare from Active Region 14048 (S15E65) starting around 2025-03-30T23:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible near the southeast limb around this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This event is faint but can be observed to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 imagery. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This event is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-04-01T17:53Z. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, jet-like CME seen accelerating to the northeast primarily in SOHO LASCO C2 and also farther to the north in STEREO A COR2; the CME is with low confidence associated with a minor eruption with northern deflection from the northeastern side of Active Region 14046 (N10E10) seen starting around 2025-04-02T08:44Z in GOES SUVI 284 imagery, but triangulation suggests that the eruption originates from the far-side, and indeed, moving field lines are seen off the northeast limb primarily in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.

Brightening and ejecta seen deflected to the east as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-04-03T03:24Z. SDO AIA imagery was in a data gap which lasted from 2025-04-02T15:52Z to 2025-04-03T04:54Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The source is a filament eruption visible along the SE limb in GOES SUVI 304 near S25E70 starting around 2025-03-04T17:32Z. Additionally moving/opening field lines are visible in GOES SUVI 171, 195, and 284, as well as brightening which is best seen in GOES SUVI 195. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The precise source is unclear, but several small instances of field line movement on can be seen just beyond the SW limb occurring between 2025-04-04T05:00Z-07:00Z in STEREO A EUVI 195 from a bright cluster of formerly numbered ARs, including ARs 4047, 4040, and 4042, which together span from about latitude S00 to S20 and longitude W90 to W110.

note: Faint CME seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and directly S in STEREO COR2A. The source is likely dimming in the far southern area of the disk, centered around S60W20, observed in SDO AIA 193 around 2025-04-04T15:00Z. This may, unlikely, be related to a C4.4 flare from AR 14502 (S23W29) which peaked at 2025-04-04T14:46Z, it is difficult to discern if this flare erupted in this deflected direction, the dimming at S60W20 is an sympathetic eruption, or if the dimming at S60W20 is entirely separate. Thus it is not currently attributed as a source, and noted for completion of the analysis.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the N in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from just beyond the NW limb. A prominence from just beyond the limb can be seen beginning to liftoff starting at 2025-04-04T16:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 and ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304 both show strong northern deflection of this eruption, with ejecta traveling nearly due north. STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 show that the prominence was centered at about N30 and spanned from W82-W92 (in SDO coordinates).

note: Faint outflow-like CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Source is narrow ejecta and brightening seen at N20W97 (SDO AIA coordinates) in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-04-04T17:45Z. This small eruption may have possibly disrupted surrounding coronal material, resulting in the faint, wide, and slow leading edge which surrounds the narrow flux rope visible in SOHO LASCO C2. This CME overlaps to the south of the preceding CME:2025-04-04T16:36Z. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-04T17:38Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Its source is likely far behind the east limb and might be indicated by the large filament behind the northeast limb moving northward, as seen in AIA SDO 304 and GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery after 2025-04-05T05:00Z, although this filament is more likely to be the source of a later, more northern, 2025-04-05T09:48Z CME.

The source could be the large filament behind the northeast limb moving northward, as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 after 2025-04-05T05:00Z, but it is unclear whether this filament is the source of this CME - or the 2025-04-05T06:36Z CME.

There is also some field line movement over the SE limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around the same time. Based on a triangulated measurement using SWPC_CAT, there would need to be a considerable amount of deflection for this candidate to be the source.

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-19T00:00Z. Also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is partially obscured by the pylon. The start of the CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting from 2025-04-18T22:38Z to 2025-04-19T02:38Z, and following the data gap the leading edge is out of the field of view. This CME is associated with an M4.4 flare peaking at 2025-04-18T23:50Z and ejecta from on/beyond the SE limb (~S29E90). A Type II radio burst was also observed. The flare and associated ejecta are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are most clearly seen in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 131. A wider, possible shock front is visible in a few early frames of SOHO LASCO C2, but quickly fades away and was determined to not be measurable. The CME experiences continued southward deflection through propagation.

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-29T23:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-29T19:23Z. The source of this event is a C7.3 flare from AR 4065 (S31W91) and subsequent filament eruption as seen exhibiting Southern deflection in SDO AIA 131, 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Wide opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow, fast CME to the SW in STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. There is currently a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source is seen as moving/opening field lines starting around 2025-05-01T08:39Z to the SW in SDO/AIA 193 and 171. An associated small filament eruption is also visible in SDO/AIA 304 and STEREO A EUVI 304 to the SW. This eruption is likely associated with old AR 14065 which rotated off the Earth-facing disk late on 2025-04-29. The estimated longitudes of the source are (~S31W110 to ~S31W125) based on calculation of average rotation and visible inspection of STEREO A EUV imagery. This active region is situated within a coronal hole which may attribute to deflection.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint narrow CME with a peculiar slanted front seen to the east in both coronagraphs. No clear source for it was found in EUV imagery, although there is continuous minor movement of field lines beyond the east limb seen in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint CME seen to the east in both coronagraphs (but only seen very faintly in a couple early timestamps of SOHO LASCO C3). No clear coronal signatures for this CME were found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2, STEREO A COR2, and faintly in GOES CCOR-1, all generally disappearing before leaving their respectively field of views. The source appears to be a minor filament eruption occurring near S30W65 seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304, and GOES SUVI 284 as various brightenings around 2025-05-02T09:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-05-03T11:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 beginning at approximately 2025-05-03T10:39Z centered at approximately N10E55, but exhibiting some Eastern deflection. Dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 211 and post eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 131 and 193.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME first seen to the southeast by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-03T16:19Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR in later frames. The source of this event is faint field line opening seen along or just beyond the SE limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint minor CME to the southwest in SOHO and STEREO A coronagraphs. Not seen in SOHO LASCO C3 because of faintness. No clear source for this CME has been found, although there might be a faint opening of field lines on/behind the SW limb in EUV STEREO A 195 imagery. However, the fit with two coronagraphs does not support the source with such high longitude.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint and narrow CME visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source appears to be a small eruption located to the NE of AR 14071 near N20E55 starting around 2025-05-04T03:10Z in SDO/AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME to the E in SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This CME is visible for a few frames before becoming too diffuse to track. The source appears to be a small filament eruption from AR 14081 as seen in SDO/AIA 304, 193, and 171 starting around 2025-05-04T07:04Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Fast, diffuse CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source appears to be a filament eruption from beyond the SW limb of STEREO A EUVI 304 starting around 2025-05-04T10:15Z. Associated moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 along the southern limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint, slow CME to the E/SE in SOHO LASCO C2. This CME is not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, nor GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is a C5.4 flare from AR 14082, best seen in SDO/AIA 131 starting around 2025-05-04T12:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Fast CME seen to the west in SOHO C2, SOHO C3, STEREO A COR2A, and GOES CCOR-1 which has no clear source on the Earth facing disk in any EUV imagers, indicating that the source is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity relative to the Earth-facing solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the west in SOHO C2, SOHO C3, STEREO A COR2A, and GOES CCOR-1 similar in appearance to the 2025-05-04T15:23Z CME which has no clear source on the Earth facing disk in any EUV imagers, indicating that the source is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity relative to the Earth-facing solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Slow, wide CME seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 / GOES CCOR1, visible in STEREO A COR2 after a data gap from 2025-05-04T21:38Z to 2025-05-05T01:53Z. Associated with an eruption occurring behind the western limb as seen best in GOES SUVI 284 imagery seen around 2025-05-05T00:08Z with strong opening field lines after 01:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME faintly seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 or GOES CCOR-1. The source is not seen in available EUV imagery, and may be farisded.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is a filament eruption centered around S25E20 with liftoff starting at 2025-05-05T08:03Z in SDO AIA 304. Eruption with dimming and opening field lines is best seen in SDO AIA 193. Post-eruptive arcades are best seen in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO AIA 335. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUV 195/304 imagery. A faint shock can be seen for a few frames of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, extending east of the bulk of the CME, but is not measurable.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is an eruption near or beyond the east limb as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-05-05T10:40Z as an ejecta of material.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. CME partially obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source is not visible in available EUV imagery and is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint narrow CME to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and in several early timestamps of C3. The CME is fully covered by the nighttime data gap in STEREO A COR2 and is likely obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. No coronal signatures for this event have been found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A narrowish CME to the northeast in SOHO coronagraph, with a thiner bulk and a possibly slightly wider shock. No clear source has been found for this CME. There is a very minor filament swirling behind/near the NE limb that is seen moving in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 304 after 2025-05-05T21:20Z, however it is not clear whether the filament eventually leaves the sun.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO COR2A, and GOES CCOR-1. The source for this CME may be some weak field line movement observed over the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-05-05T22:16Z. The CME front is not first observed leaving the occulting disk, but rather materializing around 2025-05-06T02:48Z in the LASCO C2 FOV best seen in running difference imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: A super faint CME with a faint front to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2 (with mostly left boundary visible), the front is hard to impossible to track in STEREO A COR2. No source has been found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Relatively fast, narrow eruption seen to the south-southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and farther to the east-southeast or directly southeast in STEREO A COR2; the CME is associated with a filament eruption taking place on the Earth-facing disk near S20W01 seen as a lifting off of dark plasma in GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 304 around 2025-05-06T16:30Z with bright post-eruptive arcades, especially in SDO AIA 193.

The source is a large-scale filament eruption occurring near N45W20 best seen in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO AIA 304 which begins to lift off as early as 2025-05-06T14:45Z. The full filament liftoff can be seen leaving the disk starting at 2025-05-06T17:00Z. The CME features include a faster protruding nose ahead of the bulk of the CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow, faint CME to the northwest in SOHO LASCO and to the north in STEREO A. Its source is possibly an eruption of a small filament north of of Active Region 14079 centered around (N38W30), which is seen as very faint post-eruptive arcades around 2025-06-07T11:15Z in Stereo A EUVI 195 and after 10Z in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright loop front CME with outflowing material following it to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is a filament eruption in the NE starting around 2025-05-07T11:00Z in SDO/AIA 304, 171, 131, and 193. The filament appears to stretch over the NE limb, possibly by 20 degrees based on a rough STEREO A EUVI 304 calculation. There is limited imagery available in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap for most of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Outflow-like CME seen to the northeast in SOHO C2 and STEREO A COR2 possibly associated with a partial filament eruption occurring near N37E80 between 2025-05-08T01:30Z and 02:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 193, 171, 304 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Jet CME seen to the northwest in SOHO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR1 associated with a point source eruption near the west limb as seen best in GOES SUVI 304 around 2025-05-08T02:05Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Loop CME seen only to the east in STEREO A COR2 and not seen at all in SOHO C2 or C3; the source may potentially be associated with an eruption in AR 14079 (N08W44) with strong eastern deflection in which the CME is traveling directly along the Earth-Sun line at the CME is thus not seen in SOHO, or an eruption near the northeast limb seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-05-08T05:05Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: First of three CMEs seen to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and not well seen in STEREO A COR2; the likely source is a minor eruption or series of eruptions in Active Region 14079 (N08W46) with broad moving field lines seen best in SDO AIA 171 between 2025-05-08T07:00Z and 12:00Z and some brightening post-eruptive arcades, especially in the northern extent of Active Region 4079.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Second of three CMEs seen to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and possibly seen in STEREO A COR2 as a faint and wide event to the northwest, much faster than the previous CME; the likely source is a minor eruption or series of eruptions in Active Region 14079 (N08W46) with broad moving field lines seen best in SDO AIA 171 between 2025-05-08T07:00Z and 12:00Z and some brightening post-eruptive arcades, especially in the northern extent of Active Region 4079.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Alternatively, the source could be behind the northwest limb in STEREO A seen in EUV 195 imagery starting at 14:05Z as faint movement beyond northwest limb.

A very faint partial-loop (which is the brightest in a series of similar loop-like CMEs (2025-05-09T21:36Z, 23:36, 2025-05-10T01:25, 02:00Z, 03:12, 06:36, 09:48Z). These loops are likely associated eruptive activity AR 4079. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 or GOES-CCOR1. It is possible that 21:48Z loop might be associated with the C1 flare from AR 4079 (N05W64) peaking at 20:21Z or with a very minor filament eruption seen in AIA 304 at 21:09Z (both very minor events).

The front is too faint to be traceable in STEREO A COR2 except for a couple early timestamps. The source of this CME is likely a southern filament eruption close to the SW limb extending from around (S40W75) southward and showing mostly as dimming close to the SW limb see in AIA 193 at 2025-05-10T08:42Z.

The source of this event is a small eruption along the NE limb near AR 4087 (N15E80), beginning at approx. 2025-05-11T18:37Z, as seen in GOES SUVI 304.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow faint CME with a pointy nose to the east in SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. The source is likely a filament eruption off the east limb seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-05-12T00:00Z.

N20W50 and N50E60, where as the far sided filament appears to be just beyond the NW limb. These filaments are best seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with dimming and field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. In coronagraphs, the on disk eruption appears to over shadow the far sided eruption, and they appear as one feature.

note: CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-05-23T17:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. There is no clear source for this event, as it is likely far sided. This CME heavily overlaps with far sided halo CME: 2025-05-23T16:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Fast jet with a fuzzy front seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO and to the south in STEREO A COR2 and not seen in GOES CCOR-1. Its source is likely the 2025-05-24T03:31Z eruption in the plage located in the middle of the large southern coronal hole that crossed the central meridian on 2025-05-15. The eruption was seen as brightening, dimming and post-eruptive arcades in SDO AIA 193 and 304 and is loosely centered around S45W32.

Not clearly visible in GOES CCOR-1. To satisfy this constraint - NE in LASCO, NW in STEREO - its longitude has to be between -155 and -175 degrees, so likely this is a very far-sided event. No clear source for it was found in EUV imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME overlapping a streamer blowout to the east, observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a filament eruption and brightening in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-05-25T02:54Z, and a double peaked C5.3 and C6.4 flare observed on/just beyond the east limb starting at 2025-05-25T02:50Z in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as some field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

The source of this CME is likely the M8.9 flare from Active Region 14098 (S05W50) peaking at 2025-05-25T16:30Z and the associated filament eruption seen as ejecta starting at 2025-05-25T16:43Z in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 193 and as dimming in EUVI A 195 and SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint narrow CME/outflow with unclear front overlapping with/obscured by outflows from the previous CME in this direction, faintly seen in SOHO, STEREO A COR2 and in CCOR-1. No source has been found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A relatively bright CME seen to the east in all three coronagraphs. Its source is the M1.4 flare from AR 14100 (N12E70) and the associated ejecta seen in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI/EUVI A 304 around 2025-05-26T13:21Z (ejecta directed northward). Coronal signatures include intense dimming, brightening, post-eruptive arcades and even a wide EUV wave seen almost reaching the central meridian in SDO AIA.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow fast jet to southeast in both coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). Not clearly visible in GOES CCOR-1. Its source could be a very minor ejecta seen on/close to the southeast limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-0-26T15:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME observed to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a broad opening of field lines to the northeast centered on disk around N15E61, north of AR 14100 (N08E61), observed best in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 beginning slowly around 2025-05-27T07:16Z and faster starting around 2025-05-27T08:06Z. Accompanied by some slight dimming in SDO AIA 193 well north of this central point, spanning a thin arc ~N35E90 to ~N35E40, then down to ~N08E33. This minor increase in brightening is associated with a brief post-eruptive arcade seen from Active Region 14100 and is accompanied by a long-duration post-eruptive brightening from the surrounding area near and around Active Region 14100. Long-duration post-eruptive brightening near and around Active Region 14100 can be seen in SDO AIA 131. Two brief brighter arcades forming at Active Region 14100 resulted in a C4.5 and a C5.0 flare.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint loop CME visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SE in STEREO A COR2. Source is field line movement on or near the SE limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-05-27T15:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

This eruption can be seen vaguely in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, but post eruptive arcades are seen in SDO AIA 94, 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304, more clearly.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

A possible source is an eruption from plage region 14093 (S06W61) beginning around 2025-05-30T07:12Z in SDO AIA 304 that appears to be deflected northward. The same eruption is visible in STEREO A EUVI imagery just to the SW of center disk. This would explain why the CME is not visible in COR2A (it is mostly nose on from the perspective of STEREO A and quite narrow).

note: Narrow, jet-like CME first seen to the W in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-05-30T10:23Z. CME also seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. The source is most likely an eruption that is visible near the W limb from the perspective of STEREO A. The eruption is seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 beginning around 2025-05-30T09:35Z near the W limb.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Hazy CME first seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-05-30T12:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this CME appears to be continued dimming and field line movement following a wide eruption associated with an M3.4 class flare from AR 4100. These features can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 211. This CME overlaps with earlier CME: 2025-05-30T06:38Z which is associated with the M3.4 flare, where as this event is more associated with the subsequent dimming following the flare.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Full-halo CME first seen in GOES-19 CCOR-1. Also seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 after the beginning of a downlink period with data streaming in starting at about 2025-05-31T01:00Z. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-05-30T19:09Z. The source is an M8.1 flare from AR 14100 (N12E12). A significant area of opening field lines and dimming can be seen from near AR 14100 (N12E12) in SDO AIA 193/171/131/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 beginning at 2025-05-30T23:47Z, immediately after the flare. Dimming and field line movement extends along a nearby filament which spans across most of the Earth-facing disk, stretching from approximately N30E05 to S15W35, snaking through the entire NW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk in a shape resembling the number '3'. It appears that most of the filamentary material ejected is from the upper lobe of the '3', and departs from approximately N10W15.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet like CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-31T03:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR in later frames. The source of this event may be related to a minor eruption from AR 14104 (N06E41), exhibiting Eastern deflection. This eruption can be seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with brightening seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and field line movement in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

The source of this event is likely continued dimming and field line movement seen following a large eruption from AR 14100. This dimming can be seen centered at approx. S20E05 in SDO AIA 211. No arrival signature was seen in solar wind at L1, however this CME may have been swept into the combined front by a later faster 2025-05-31T14:23Z CMe.

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-05-31T09:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR in later frames. There is no abundantly clear source for this event. There is a small region of brightening and field line movement from AR 14100 (N15E08) beginning at approx. 2025-05-31T13:34Z as seen in SDO AIA 94 and 211 that may be associated with this CME.

note: Faint loop CME first distinguishable as a coherent front to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-06-01T18:00Z. There is no clear source in available UV imagery. There are several extremely faint, outflow-like fronts seen to the SW around this time. This front is the most cohesive and is visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: CME visible to the N in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and slightly to the NE in STEREO COR2. The source is uncertain, but may be a wide area of slowly opening field lines visible in the NW portion of the Earth-facing disk, centered at approximately N50 and extending from W90 to possibly as far as E10 (it is difficult to tell given the faintness of the field line movement on the disk) as seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting as early as 2025-06-02T11:30Z. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-06-02T23:53Z to 2025-06-03T00:53Z.

note: A slow CME to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2, seen more brightly in COR2A and appearing as a faint partial halo in CCOR-1. Its start time could possibly be even earlier, but the clear front is seen closer to 2025-06-03T07:48Z. Its source could be an eruption of a filament in the north/northeast, seen in SDO AIA 193/304 and EUVI A 195/304/284 starting at ~2025-06-03T01:21Z. Initial dimming and faint post-eruptive arcades are centered around ~(N20E01), but later the dimming is seen migrating/expanding eastwardly through the rest of the morning, and settling on a large circular area centered ~N35E15 by 2025-06-03T12:20Z.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the Northeast by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-06-05T08:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a far sided filament eruption seen faintly in GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement is also visible along the NE limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

The source is nearly continuous, gradual, and wide field line movement seen on and near the south limb of the Earth-facing disk as seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption is preceded by a slower outflow of material which was similar in appearance, though more diffuse, and sourced from at or near the same location near the southern limb of the Earth-facing disk.

Very subtle field line movement in the vicinity of N35W75 can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195, but there are several subtle instances of field line movement in the area of the disk, therefore it is difficult to identify an exact source.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to a filament eruption visible beyond the southwest limb in SDO AIA 304 imagery which hovers for a few hours before lifting off around 2025-06-08T05:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption visible near the northeast limb starting around 2025-06-08T12:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-06-08T21:36Z. CME is also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1. CME is seen to the NNE in STEREO A COR2 for two very faint frames. There is some significant deflection toward the N later into the propagation through the FOV of SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is like an eruption from over the NE limb visible in SDO AIA 304 beginning around 2025-06-08T21:22Z. Source is a filament eruption beyond the NW limb as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, and seen close to the limb in STEREO A EUVI 304. There are two lobes of this CME, each corresponding to a piece of filament that erupted. Both pieces of filamentary material can be seen erupting simultaneously in GOES SUVI 304 imagery, so both lobes are therefore considered as one CME. The filament is located at latitude N40 and spanned from approximately W90 to W130. Gradual liftoff is seen starting as early as 2025-07-05T06:23Z in GOES SUVI 304. There is a data gap in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery such that the start of the filament liftoff is not captured.

note: A faint CME with a fuzzy front dissipating soon (or father a sequence of fuzzy faint fronts following each other almost immediately). The CME is directed to the west-northwest seen in SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs. Its initial front is too faint to be seen in C3, but it can faintly be seen as one of the follow-up fronts in C3. The source of this CME is a filament eruption happening behind the northwest limb as seen from STEREO A EUVI 195/304 - especially note the wide opening of field lines/restructuring of magnetic field on/behind the limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 starting at 2025-07-06T17:05Z, and a bit later a minor but bright post-eruptive peeking from behind the west limb in EUVI A 304. SDO AIA 304/171 and GOES SUVI 304 also possibly see this eruption - but as a loop-like filament that seems to slowly depart the limb around 17:18Z, after first starting to rise as a sizable loop some time as early as 15:30Z.

note: Faint, diffuse CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source may be weak field line movement near/just inside the SE limb starting as early as 2025-07-07T13:59Z in GOES SUVI 284, and slow dimming in SDO AIA 193. This front is preceeded by a faint, too diffuse to track outflow beginning at 2025-07-07T13:36Z in LASCO C2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME first seen in the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-07-07T22:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is an area of slow field line opening seen originating from along the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 193 beginning at 2025-07-07T21:31Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME first seen to the SW in GOES CCOR-1 beginning at 2025-07-07T23:00Z, as well as in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen originating from near AR 14127 S20W75 seen beginning at approx. 2025-07-07T22:24Z in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and more NNE in STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption on or just beyond the NE limb around N22, with an M2.4 flare visible in SDO AIA 171 which began at 2025-07-08T03:42Z. Also observed well in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284 as wide field line opening, an EUV wave, and a brief post eruptive arcade. This source eruption may have triggered simultaneous fronts in other directions, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:36Z (NE more in ecliptic) and CME 2025-07-08T04:48Z (far north).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to overlap with bright CME 2025-07-08T04:24Z. The source is likely sympathetic with an eruption on or just beyond the NE limb around N22 that had an M2.4 flare visible in SDO AIA 171 which began at 2025-07-08T03:42Z, also observed well in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284 as wide field line opening, an EUV wave, and a brief post eruptive arcade. A small filament ejecta near N20E70 lifts off concurrently in SDO AIA 304, and is another candidate source, although it erupts alongside the larger eruption on the limb. This CME front appears to be triggered alongside simultaneous fronts in other directions from this same eruption, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:24Z (bright NE bulk) and CME 2025-07-08T04:48Z (far north).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME observed to the far north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, blocked by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source is likely sympathetic with an eruption on or just beyond the NE limb around N22 that had an M2.4 flare visible in SDO AIA 171 which began at 2025-07-08T03:42Z, also observed well in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284 as wide field line opening, an EUV wave, and a brief post eruptive arcade. This front is not from the main ejecta of this eruption, but appears to be triggered alongside simultaneous fronts in other directions, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:24Z (bright NE bulk) and CME 2025-07-08T04:36Z (NE, more in ecliptic).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is visible to the west in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 or GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and may be related to an opening of field lines on or beyond the western limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 imagery starting around 2025-07-09T10:55Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is very faint but visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is unknown and likely far-sided, but may be related to an eruption visible on or slightly beyond the southwest limb near latitude S50 as seen in STEREO A EUVI imagery starting around 2025-07-09T11:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the northwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is blocked by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk that align with the direction of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The CME start time is actually 2025-07-09T13:25Z (4 hours earlier than the start time in DONKI). This is because SOHO LASCO was not available on the day when the CME was analyzed and entered into DONKI. CME with a flux rope clearly seen in coronagraphs, first seen to the NW in GOES CCOR-1 starting around 2025-07-09T17:30Z. CME is also seen to the N in STEREO A COR2. CME was originally covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, but LASCO eventually backfilled. A possible source for this CME is a filament eruption starting to the SW of AR 14137 beginning around 2025-07-09T15:30Z and moving eastward - faint ejecta can be seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA 304. If this candidate is the source of the CME, there is some significant deflection to the NW.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint CME with two lobes seen to the north in SOHO LASCO and in GOES CCOR-1 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 and closely following the wider, slightly slower, preceding CME: 2025-07-09T17:30Z. This CME is partially obscured by the pylon in C3. Its source has not been found, but is likely the same Active Region 4137 that produced the preceding, 2025-07-09T17:30Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME first seen to the E in GOES CCOR-1 starting around 2025-07-09T21:20Z. CME is not seen in STEREO A COR2 and is covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There is not a good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk, so the source is possibly far-sided.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and SW in STEREO A COR2. No source is observed in SDO, GOES, or STEREO A imagery, which combined with the triangulation of coronagraph imagery concludes that this source is far-sided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SW in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from beyond the SE limb from the perspective of SDO AIA and GOES SUVI and beyond the SW limb from the perspective of STEREO A EUVI. Diffuse ejecta from beyond the SE limb can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting as early as 2025-07-11T09:52Z. In STEREO A EUVI 304, there may possibly be a rising loop from beyond the SW limb seen between the frames with timestamps 2025-07-11T07:45Z-08:15Z, followed by wider opening field lines between the frames with timestamps 2025-07-11T08:15Z-08:45Z. The first available frame of SOHO LASCO C2 in which the leading edge is well defined is the frame at timestamp 2025-07-11T10:24Z after a brief gap caused by a scheduled calibration of SOHO LASCO.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the NW seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and obscured by pylon in C3; not really seen in other coronagraphs. It is the second faint front (the earlier, 03Z front is even fainter and disappears really quickly in C2 imagery). Source is likely a slowly developing, messy eruption near AR 4037, centered ~(N32W23), starting as early as 2025-07-1tT00:54Z and lasting through the whole morning (at least to 5Z). The eruption location seems to move further west with time. Coronal signatures include developing faint dimming and faint post-eruptive arcades, as seen in SDO AIA 193/304, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: A relatively narrow CME with a messy front visible to SSW in white light (as well as in running difference) imagery in all three coronagraphs. Seen more to the south and more faintly in STEREO A COR2. Its likely source is a filament seen erupting starting at 2025-07-12T08:45Z near the SW limb, as seen in SDO AIA imagery, centered very approximately at (S35W60). The source is seen in more detail in STEREO A EUV 304/195 imagery than in other EUV imagers: in STEREO EUVI 195 two simultaneous eruptions cam be seen - one in the AR 4134 (~S23W90), and the other in the filament located SE of this AR (~S35W45).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME with fuzzy front seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery (too fuzzy and faint to be traced in C3 and GOES CCOR-1), and so far covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. It disappears from C2 imagery after several timestamps because of it's faintness. Its source could be an eruption in former Active Region 14134 (S21W95) that is now behind the west limb. The eruption is seen after 2025-07-12T15:30Z as an opening of field lines behind the limb in SDO AIA 193, GOES SUVI 284 and as bright post eruptive arcade seen on/behind the limb in SUVI 304. Eruption also likely seen on disk in STEREO A EUV imagery before the data gap in STEREO A, best seen as a brightening in Active Region 14134 starting around 2025-07-12T15:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Fast CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR1 but so far covered by the gap in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. Its source could be an eruption in the NE quadrant, with medium size dimming seen in AIA 193 starting after 2025-07-12T12:00Z and centered around (N20E52). There is also activity in AR 4136 (N19E32) at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME with a narrower bulk and a wider, fainter possible shock front visible to the NNW in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and to the N in STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Very narrow jet-like CME (less than 10 degree half-width) first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T16:12Z. CME is only visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and is much easier to see in running difference imagery. CME fades before leaving FOV of SOHO LASCO C2. The source is likely a small eruption from on/beyond the NE limb around 2025-07-13T14:42Z best seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T18:36Z. CME is also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and very faintly in STEREO A COR2. A possible source of this CME is a small eruption best seen near the SW limb in SDO AIA 304 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:03Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T19:24Z. CME is also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is most likely some opening field lines from beyond the NW limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:16Z. CME likely combines with following, faster CME: 2025-07-13T22:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T22:12Z. CME is also seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is most likely an eruption from AR 14137 beginning around 2025-07-13T21:44Z best seen in GOES SUVI 284. The eruption can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and STEREO A EUVI 304 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:35Z followed by an EUV wave. CME collides and likely combines with previous, slower CME: 2025-07-13T19:24Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk. Leading edge is not visible in STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but may be subtle field line movement seen on or beyond the SE limb GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint flux rope CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Exact source is uncertain, but is very likely associated with continued outflow to the NW from near AR 4137 (N19W81) or beyond the NW limb, following the eruptions associated with CME:2025-07-13T19:24Z and CME:2025-07-13T22:12Z which were both to the NW as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is an eruption from former Active Region 14134 (S22W118) at 2025-07-14T13:45Z seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. This eruption immediately triggers the eruption of a nearby filament which spans from about S45W72 to S20W102 with liftoff starting at about 2025-07-14T15:15Z as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines and ejecta can be seen on the SW limb, originating from AR 14134, and filamentary ejecta can be seen departing from the SW limb with heavy southward deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304/284 and SDO AIA 304/193/171/131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the South by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-07-14T19:38Z, as well as by GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a large amount of prominence material leaving the sun, following an earlier eruption from AR 14134 and resulting CME: 2025-07-14T14:36Z. Prominence material is seen beginning to leave the sun with this earlier eruption beginning at approx. 2025-07-14T15:15Z. This material then slowly stretches Southward along the Western limb and out of the field of view in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304 before finally fully disconnecting from the sun at approx. 2025-07-14T20:36Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1
